urango}}\n||8||1||3\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Nayarit}}\n||8||1||2\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Zacatecas}}\n||7||1||1\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Campeche}}\n||6||0||1\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Tlaxcala}}\n||8||0||1\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Colima}}\n||4||0||1\n|- style=\"text-align:left; padding-left:8px;\" class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"width:360px;\" colspan=\"6\"| '''Source:''' \n<small>Secretar\u00eda de Salud (2020).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gob.mx/salud/es/archivo/prensa?idiom=es&order=DESC&page=1 |title=Prensa &#124; Archivo &#124; Secretar\u00eda de Salud &#124; Gobierno |publisher=gob.mx |date= |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref><br>\nGeological and Atmospheric Research Institute <ref name=\"iigea1\">{{cite web|url=http://iigea.com/amag/covid-19/ |title=COVID-19 Seguimiento \u2013 IIGEA |publisher=Iigea.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n</small>\n|}\n\n=== Cases per 100,000 inhabitants ===\n\n[[File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Mexico per 100,000 inhabitants.svg|thumb|right|251xpx| Map of the COVID-19 outbreak in Mexico per 100,000 inhabitants as of 2 April 2020.<br/>\n{{legend|#fee5d9|<0.1 per 100,000}}{{legend|#fcbba1|\u22650.1 per 100,000}}{{legend|#fc9272|\u22650.5 per 100,000}}{{legend|#fb6a4a|\u22651.0 per 100,000}}{{legend|#de2d26|\u22651.5 per 100,000}}{{legend|#a50f15|\u22652.0 per 100,000}}{{legend|#630606|\u22653.0 per 100,000}} {{legend|#450404|\u22655.0 per 100,000}} {{legend|#310303|\u22657.0 per 100,000}}]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display: inline-table; font-size:90%; text-align:right;\"\n|+ <big> As of April 3</big>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"  style=\"text-align:left; width:140px;\"|State\n! style=\"width:60px;\"| Cases\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Population{{efn|In 2015.}}\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Cases per 100,000 inhabitants{{efn|Calculated by dividing the number of cases by the total population of the state and multiplying the result by 100,000.}}\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:right; padding-right:18px;\" scope=\"row\" | 1688\n! style=\"text-align:right; padding-right:18px;\" scope=\"row\" | 119,530,753\n! style=\"text-align:right; padding-right:18px;\" scope=\"row\" | 1.4\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Mexico City}}\n||384||8,918,653||4.3\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Quintana Roo}}\n||65||1,501,562||4.3\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Aguascalientes}}\n||48||1,312,544||3.7\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Tabasco}}\n||73||2,395,272||3.0\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Baja California Sur}}\n||21||712,029||2.9\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Yucat\u00e1n}}\n||58||2,097,175||2.8\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Coahuila}}\n||70||2,954,915||2.4\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Puebla}}\n||109||6,168,883||1.8\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Nuevo Le\u00f3n}}\n||85||5,119,504||1.7\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Quer\u00e9taro}}\n||35||2,038,372||1.7\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Sinaloa}}\n||51||2,966,321||1.7\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Baja California}}\n||52||3,315,766||1.6\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Jalisco}}\n||116||7,844,830||1.5\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" | {{Flag2|San Luis Potos\u00ed}}\n||35||2,717,820||1.3\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|State of Mexico}}\n||177||16,187,608||1.1\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Hidalgo}}\n||30||2,858,359||1.0\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Guanajuato}}\n||52||5,853,677||0.9\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Sonora}}\n||22||2,850,330||0.8\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Campeche}}\n||6||899,931||0.7\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Guerrero}}\n||24||3,533,251||0.7\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Nayarit}}\n||8||1,181,050||0.7\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Colima}}\n||4||711,235||0.6\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Morelos}}\n||12||1,903,811||0.6\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Oaxaca}}\n||22||3,967,889||0.6\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Tlaxcala}}\n||8||1,272,847||0.6\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Durango}}\n||8||1,754,754||0.5\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Michoac\u00e1n}}\n||24||4,584,471||0.5\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Tamaulipas}}\n||16||3,441,698||0.5\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Veracruz}}\n||35||8,112,505||0.4\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Zacatecas}}\n||7||1,579,209||0.4\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Chiapas}}\n||18||5,217,908||0.3\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Chihuahua}}\n||12||3,556,574||0.3\n|- style=\"text-align:left; padding-left:8px;\" class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"width:360px;\" colspan=\"6\"| '''Source:''' \n<small>Secretariat of Health (2020).<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/><br>\nGeological and Atmospheric Research Institute <ref name=\"iigea1\"/><br>National Institute of Statistics and Geography <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cuentame.inegi.org.mx/poblacion/habitantes.aspx?tema=P |title=N\u00famero de habitantes. Cu\u00e9ntame de M\u00e9xico |publisher=Cuentame.inegi.org.mx |date=2005-04-02 |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== Curve of infection ===\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=600\n|height=400\n|colors=#FF4343\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend\n<!-- PLease clipboard copy the \"}x=...\" and \"y1=...\" lines from the log plot of total cases when you update these charts -->\n\n<!-- Search string CASES_X -->\n|x= Feb 28, Feb 29, Mar 1, Mar 6, Mar 7, Mar 11, Mar 12, Mar 13, Mar 14, Mar 15, Mar 16, Mar 17, Mar 18, Mar 19, Mar 20, Mar 21, Mar 22, Mar 23, Mar 24, Mar 25, Mar 26, Mar 27, Mar 28, Mar 29, Mar 30, Mar 32, Apr 1, Apr 2, Apr 3, Apr 4\n\n<!-- Search string CASES_Y -->\n|y1= 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 11, 15, 26, 41, 53, 82, 93, 118, 164, 203, 251, 316, 367, 405, 475, 585, 717, 848, 993, 1094, 1215, 1378, 1510, 1688, 1890\n\n|yScaleType=<!--log This is the line that makes this plot have a log axis, so leave it blank here!-->\n|y1Title=Total confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n== Phases ==\nAccording to the Secretariat of Health, there are three phases before the disease (COVID-19) can be considered as an epidemic in the country:<ref name=\"phases\">{{cite web|url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexicos-covid-19-contingency-plan-three-key-phases-fight-coronavirus-outbreak|title= Mexico's covid-19 contingency plan: three key phases to fight the coronavirus outbreak|author=Teresa Moreno|date=March 14, 2020|website=El Universal}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display: inline-table; font-size:90%; text-align:right;\"\n|-\n! colspan =\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Phase\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | Time period\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | Description \n! rowspan=\"2\" | Ref\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" | Start \n! style=\"text-align:center;\" | End\n|-\n! 1\u00b0\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Viral Import\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | February 28, 2020\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | March 23, 2020<ref name=\"phase2\">{{cite web|url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/covid-19-mexico-has-entered-second-phase-its-contingency-plan |title= Covid-19: mexico has entered the second phase of its contingency plan |author=Newsroom & Agencies|date=March 24, 2020|website=El Universal}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | \n*People with the virus caught the disease outside Mexico and there are no cases of local transmission.\n*There is a limited number of people infected with the virus.\n*There are no strict restrictions for greeting people. \n*Public events in closed or open spaces are still allowed.\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:left\" | <ref name=\"phases\" />\n|-\n! 2\u00b0\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Community Transmission\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | March 24, 2020<ref name=\"phase2\" />\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[TBA]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Community transmission cases are reported between people who have not had contact with foreigners.\n*The number of confirmed cases increases rapidly.\n*Massive public events are canceled both in open and closed spaces.\n*School classes are suspended and people are encouraged to work from home. \n|-\n! 3\u00b0\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | Epidemic\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[TBA]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\" | [[TBA]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\" |\n* Thousands of cases are reported in multiple locations across the country.\n*Schools and workplaces with active outbreaks would have no activities.\n* It requires the implementation of stricter health protocols.\n* In the worst case scenario it would be required a general quarantine of the population.\n|}\n\n==Economic effects==\n{{See also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe [[National Institute of Statistics and Geography (Mexico)|INEGI]] says the unemployment rate increased from 3.6% in January 2020 to 3.7% in February 2020. The informal sector increased to 56.3% in February compared to 56.0% in February 2019.<ref>[https://www.tvazteca.com/aztecanoticias/finanzas/notas/aumenta-el-desempleo-en-mexico?fbclid=IwAR2eO0b2MXeWkJ0JegBEJNrXILvvAH1frrw1IFAF47gKBLfQoAVBA5LaJas Unemployment increases in Mexico] {{in lang|es}} Azteca Noticias, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[Mexican Stock Exchange]] fell to a record low on 10 March due to fears of the coronavirus and because of [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|falling oil prices]]. The [[Bank of Mexico|Bank of Mexico (Banxico)]] stepped in to prop up the value of the peso, which fell 14% to 22.929 per US dollar.<ref name=\"banixco\"/> World markets are seeing falls similar to those of 1987.<ref>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/blogs/colegio-de-contadores-publicos-de-mexico-ac/historico-el-covid-19-provoca-la-mayor-crisis-en Historical! COVID-19 causes the biggest crisis in global financial markets] {{in lang|es}} by COLEGIO DE CONTADORES P\u00daBLICOS DE M\u00c9XICO, A.C., Dinero en Imagen, 18 Mar 2020</ref> [[Moody's Investors Service]] predicted that the economy will contract 5.2% during the first trimester of the year and 3.7% by the end of the year.<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/25/economia-de-mexico-caera-37-por-coronavirus-moodys/ Mexico's economy will drop 3.7% due to coronavirus: Moody\u2019s] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 25 Mar 2020</ref> Banxico announced on 1 April that foreign investors have withdrawn MXN $150 billion (US $,6.3 billion) from Mexico, mostly in ''Certificados de la Tesorer\u00eda'' ((Treasury Certificates, Cetes) since February 27 when the first COVID-19 case in Mexico was diagnosed. The problem is compounded by the low oil price, only US $10.37 per barrel, a 20.29% drop since the beginning of the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]].<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/04/01/coronavirus-en-mexico-extranjeros-retiran-150-mmdp-del-pais-por-covid-19/ Coronavirus in Mexico: foreigners withdraw 150 mmdp from the country for COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} Infoabe Mexico, 1 April 2020</ref> \n\nOn 24 March, [[Grupo Modelo]], makers of [[Corona (beer)|Corona beer]], promised to donate 300,000 bottles of antibacterial gel to the [[Mexican Social Security Institute|Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS)]].<ref>[https://www.sinembargo.mx/24-03-2020/3754411?fbclid=IwAR2qx4vzr-sOgF5mF2IjD2EFAz5_Tq-OZAFpF6irpufZBsavsysjswaMYLk Grupo Modelo donar\u00e1 300 mil botellas de gel antibacterial al IMSS para combatir al COVID-19]{{in lang|es}} Sin Embargo, 24 Mar 2020</ref> The ''Conacintra'' (National Chamber of the Processing Industry) announced on 2 April they were suspending all beer production in the country, as breweries are not an essential industry and there was sufficient supply in the country for a month.<ref>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cartera/coronavirus-no-se-producira-cerveza-durante-un-mes-informa-canacintra Beer will not be produced for a month; Not an essential activity: Canacintra] {{in lang|es}} El Universal, 2 Apr 2020</ref> Tequila producers plan to stay open.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-mexico-tequila/mexican-tequila-makers-unlike-brewers-plan-to-keep-up-production-exports-idUSKBN21M0SU Mexican tequila makers, unlike brewers, plan to keep up production, exports] Reuters, 4 Apr 2020</ref>\n\nThe ''Consejo Nacional Empresarial Tur\u00edstico'' (National Tourism Business Council, CNET) sent two letters in March to [[Alfonso Romo]], Chief of Staff to the President, outlining the importance of tourism to the economy and asking for government support for the sector. Tourism provides 4 million jobs in Mexico, and 93% of the companies have ten or fewer employees. COVID-19 has forced the closure of 4,000 hotels (52,400 rooms) and 2,000 restaurants, while the airline industry has lost MXN $30 billion (US $1.3 billion).<ref>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/carlos-velazquez/el-cnet-pide-apoyo-mientras-sus-empresas-salvan-empleos/120918 The CNET asks for support while their companies save jobs] {{in lang|en}} by Carlos Velazquez, Dinero en Imagen, 26 Mar 2020</ref> Tourism accounts for 10% of [[Gross domestic product|Gross domestic product (GDP)]] in the world.<ref>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/maricarmen-cortes/turismo-en-riesgo-el-10-del-pib-mundial/120916 Tourism: 10% of world GDP at risk] {{in lang|en}} by Maricarmen Cortes, Dinero en Imagen, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nThe association of car dealers, ADMA, predicts a decrease in sales in Mexico between 16% and 25% this year.<ref>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/jose-yuste/desesperacion-de-industrias/120857?utm_source=dineroenimagen_desktop&utm_campaign=relacionados&utm_medium=article Despair of industries] {{in lang|en}} by Jos\u00e9 Yuste, Dinero en Imagen, 25 Mar 2020</ref> [[J.D. Power]] estimated a 20% decrease, 264,000 vehicles, in Mexico and a 15% drop across the world.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com.mx/economia-caida-venta-autos-mexico-20-coronavirus/ Car sales in Mexico will fall 20% due to coronavirus: JD Power] {{in lang|es}} Forbes Mexico, 1 April 2020</ref> The [[Coparmex|Employers Confederation of the Mexican Republic (COPARMEX)]] criticized the government on 29 March for not suspending the payment of taxes, saying the government does not care about unemployment. Fernando Trevi\u00f1o N\u00fa\u00f1ez, president of the organization, explained that businesses cannot afford to pay salaries for more than three months without receiving income.<ref>[https://www.milenio.com/negocios/sin-rumbo-el-gobierno-federal-ante-la-pandemia-coparmex Sin rumbo, el gobierno federal ante la pandemia: Coparmex] {{in lang|es}} by  Ang\u00e9lica Tenahua, Milenio, 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nPanic buying in mid-March is causing shortages in Mexico of [[Hydroxychloroquine]] and [[azithromycin]], which U.S. President Donald Trump, with no backing from the scientific or medical communities, says is helpful in preventing COVID-19. The ''Comisi\u00f3n Federal para la Protecci\u00f3n de Riesgos Sanitarios'' (Federal Commission for the Protection of Health Risks, Cofepris) has put controls on the sale of both products. Hidroxicloroquina is used in the treatment of [[malaria]], [[lupus]] and [[rheumatoid arthritis]]. Plaquenil tablets are produced in Mexico by the French company [[Sanofi]]; the raw material comes from [[Hungary]]. Shortages of medicine for these diseases can be expected soon.<ref name=panic>[https://www.dineroenimagen.com/jose-yuste/compras-de-panico-escasean-la-hidroxicloroquina/120913 Compras de p\u00e1nico escasean la hidroxicloroquina] {{in lang|en}} by Jos\u00e9 Yuste, Dinero en Imagen, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nGasoline and diesel fuel importers have not noted a decrease in demand since the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic, and they fear that health precautions could cause fuel delays at ports of entry. [[Watco Companies]] said that cargo on the [[Houston Ship Channel]] for delivery to San Luis Potos\u00ed increased 25% in March compared to January. Mexico imports 65% of its gasoline.<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/26/crecen-temores-entre-importadores-de-gasolina-por-caida-en-la-demanda/ Fears Grow Among Gasoline Importers Due to Demand Drop] {{in lang|en}} By Amy Stillman & Jeffrey Bair, Bloomberg/Inforbae, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nSome financial analysts say there has been too little, too late. Carlos Serrano of [[BBVA M\u00e9xico]] predicts a 4.5% economic contraction in 2020, while analysts at [[Capital Economics]] in London argue that the government has to do more to support the economy. They forecast a 6% contraction this year. HR Ratings, Latin America\u2019s first credit rating agency, said that the performance of the economy this year will depend on the government\u2019s response to the COVID-19 crisis.<ref>{{cite web |website=Mexico News Daily|title=While WHO praises virus response, financial analysts say it's too slow|date=March 26, 2020|language=en |url=https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/coronavirus/who-praises-virus-response/}}</ref>\n\t\nAuthorities are concerned about supermarket robberies. A gang of 70 people robbed a grocery store in [[Tec\u00e1mac]], State of Mexico, on March 23, and a gang of 30 looted a supermarket in [[Oaxaca City]] on March 24. Calls for supermarket looting, warning of food shortages, are making the rounds of social media.<ref>[https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/30-break-into-and-loot-oaxaca-supermarket-2/ 30 people break into and loot Oaxaca supermarket] Mexico News Daily, 25 Mar 2020  [https://apnews.com/5625bb27578887acbb834bd99bfccaaa Mexico police investigate store robberies as virus spreads] AP, 25 March 2020</ref> Four such social media groups in Tijuana were broken up in Baja California on 29 March.<ref>[https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/frustran-saqueos-a-tiendas-en-tijuana/ar-BB11SNZj Frustran saqueos a tiendas en Tijuana] {{in lang|es}} Excelsior, 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n*9 January, 2020 \u2013 A travel advisory for people traveling to or from China was issued.<ref name=indigo />\n*22 January \u2013 The [[Secretariat of Health (Mexico)|Secretariat of Health]] issued a statement saying that the novel coronavirus COVID-19 did not present a danger to Mexico.<ref name=indigo>{{cite web |url=https://www.reporteindigo.com/piensa/el-nuevo-virus-coronavirus-no-representa-un-peligro-para-mexico/ |title=El Nuevo Virus Coronavirus No Representa Un Peligro Para M\u00e9xico |trans-title=The New Coronavirus Does Not Represent a Danger for Mexico |language=Spanish |work=Reporte de Indigo |date=22 January 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n*30 January \u2013 The Government of Mexico designed a ''Preparation and Response Plan'' that was made by the National Committee for Health Safety, a working group led by Secretariat of Health composed by different health entities aiming to act upon the imminent arrival of the pandemic. This group carried out a series of alert measures, rehabilitation and updating of epidemiological regulations based on the International Health Regulations.<ref name=salud>{{cite web|url=http://www.gob.mx/salud/prensa/033-mexico-esta-preparado-para-enfrentar-coronavirus-2019-ncov|title=M\u00e9xico est\u00e1 preparado para enfrentar coronavirus (2019-nCoV) (Mexico is prepared to face coronavirus)|publisher=Secretariat of Health|date=|website=gob.mx|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n*5 March \u2013 The National Governors' Conference (Conago) met to discuss the coronavirus outbreak. The directors of INSABI, IMSS and ISSSTE also participated.<ref name=conago/>\n*6 March \u2013 [[Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell Ram\u00edrez]] led the first daily press conference on COVID-19.<ref name=nat_coun_health />\n*10 March \u2013 As the stock market and the price of oil fell, \u2018\u2018Banxico\u2019\u2019 stepped in to prop up the value of the peso, which had fallen 14%.<ref name=banixco />\n*13 March \u2013 The National Autonomous University of Mexico suspended in-person classes. Authorities canceled or postponed major tourist events in Guadalajara and Merida.<ref name=cancelations />\n*14 March\n**The SEP announced that all sporting and civic events in schools would be canceled<ref name=sep /> and that Easter break, originally planned from 6 to 17 April, would be extended from 20 March to 20 April.<ref name=\"Prevention Easter break in schools\" /> On 31 March the school closings were extended through 30 April.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Casos-positivos-de-COVID-19-en-Mexico-ascienden-a-mil-215-20200331-0171.html Positive cases of COVID-19 in Mexico amount to 1,215] {{in lang|es}} Informador, 31 Mar 2020</ref>\n**The SCHP announced it was taking measures to prevent a 0.5% fall in GDP.<ref name=schp /> \n**The \u2018\u2018Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Nuevo Le\u00f3n\u2019\u2019 (UANL) suspended classes for its more than 206,000 students starting on March 17.<ref name=uanl />\n*15 March \u2013 [[List of heads of government of Mexico City|Mexico City mayor]] Claudia Sheinbaum declared that Mexico City expected to spend an extra MXN $100 million to prevent the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=sheinbaum />\n*18 March \u2013 Authorities announced that they were looking for hundreds of citizens who might be carriers of the coronavirus, especially in the states of Puebla, Jalisco, Aguascalientes and Guerrero. The Autonomous University of Guerrero (UAGRO) in Chilpancingo closed after a female student tested positive for the virus.<ref name=look />\n*22 March\n**Bars, nightclubs, movie theaters and museums were closed in Mexico City.<ref name=bars /> \n**Governor Alfaro Ram\u00edrez announces that [[Jalisco]] and seven other states would block flights from areas such as that had a high rate of coronavirus. He also said that they would purchase 25,000 testing kits.<ref name=planes />\n**Governor [[Jaime Rodr\u00edguez Calder\u00f3n]] of Nuevo Le\u00f3n said he will not rule out the use of force to get people to stay at home.<ref>[https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/el-bronco-no-descarta-usar-fuerza-publica-para-que-se-cumpla-aislamiento/1371423 \u2018El Bronco\u2019 no descarta usar fuerza p\u00fablica para que se cumpla aislamiento] {{in lang|es}} by ARACELY GARZA, Reuters/Excelsior, 22 Mar 2020, retrieved 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n*23 March\n**The WHO announced that Mexico had entered into the community contact phase of infection.<ref name=who />\n**The National Campaign of Healthy Distancing, a national program of non-pharmaceutical measures based on [[social distancing]], began.<ref name=social/> A media campaign led by \"Susana Distancia\", who is a fictional female superhero aiming to promote social distancing, was launched.<ref name=susana /> \"Susana Distancia\" is in fact a [[Word play|wordplay]] roughly meaning \"(maintaining) a healthy distance\".\n**Access to supermarkets, drugstores and convenience stores in Coahuila was limited to one person per family, and the temperature of that person was taken before entering.<ref name=supermarket />\n*24 March \u2013 President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador|L\u00f3pez Obrador]] announced that Mexico had entered Phase 2 of the coronavirus pandemic, in effect until April 30. Gatherings of more than 100 people were prohibited, and both the [[Mexican Army]] and the [[Mexican Navy]] would participate.<ref name=amlo_phase2 />\n*25 March\n**President L\u00f3pez Obrador ordered the Mexican Air Force to rescue Mexicans trapped in Argentina.<ref name=airforce /> \n**[[PROFECO|Office of the Federal Prosecutor for the Consumer (Profeco)]] closed two businesses in [[Tijuana]], Baja California, for price-gouging.<ref name=profecobc /> \n**In Mexico City, Claudia Sheinbaum announced financial support for families and micro industries affected by the pandemic, and she suspended automobile smog checks through April 19. She closed movie theaters, bars, nightclubs, gyms and other entertainment centers.<ref name=finsupport />\n**The government announced that it would continue receiving [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|cruise ships]] \u201cfor humanitarian reasons,\u201d but that passengers would be individually \"fumigated\" before being taken directly to airports to be returned to their home countries. The protocol will apply to the {{ship|MS|Europa}}, currently docked in Puerta Vallarta.<ref name=sea>[https://apnews.com/01aea6b6217f0464be47180c27af389f Mexico will receive cruise ships, but fumigate passengers] AP, 25 Mar 2020</ref>\n*26 March\n**President L\u00f3pez Obrador addressed the [[G20|Group of Twenty]] regarding medical supplies and trade and tariffs.<ref name=g20 /> The federal government announced it would suspend most sectors' activities from 26 March to 19 April.<ref name=suspend_govt /> \n**The Secretary of Health estimated that Phase 3 of the pandemic, when the number of cases reaches its peak, will be about 19 April.<ref name=peak /> \n**Authorities in Chihuahua announced that it would start to quarantine migrants who were returned to the Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez border crossing.<ref name=chi />\n**The ''Comisi\u00f3n Federal para la Protecci\u00f3n de Riesgos Sanitarios'' (Federal Commission for the Protection of Health Risks, Cofepris) put controls on the sale of hidroxicloroquina and azithromycin, used in the treatment of malaria, lupus]] and rheumatoid arthritis, but not shown to be effective against [[COVID-19]]. Nonetheless, panic buying of these medicines is likely to soon lead to a shortage.<ref name=panic />\n*27 March\n** President L\u00f3pez Obrador practiced social distancing during his tour in [[Nayarit]]. The president had been widely criticized for shaking hands, kissing and hugging as he met with people.<ref name=distance>[https://politica.expansion.mx/presidencia/2020/03/27/en-gira-por-nayarit-amlo-aplica-sana-distancia-recomendada-por-coronavirus En gira por Nayarit, AMLO aplica \"sana distancia\" recomendada por coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} Expansi\u00f3n Politica, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n**The federal government bought 5,000 [[ventilator]]s from China.<ref name=ventilator>[https://politica.expansion.mx/presidencia/2020/03/27/gobierno-compra-5-000-ventiladores-a-china-para-enfrentar-coronavirus Gobierno compra 5,000 ventiladores a China para enfrentar coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} Expansi\u00f3n Politica, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n**Profeco (Office of the Federal Prosecutor for the Consumer) announced it would fine merchants who unfairly raised the prices on household goods.<ref name=fine />\n**[[V\u00edctor Villalobos Ar\u00e1mbula]], [[Secretariat of Agriculture and Rural Development (Mexico)|Secretary of Agriculture and Rural Development (SADER)]] met with food producers to discuss guaranteeing the food supply in spite of the pandemic.<ref>[https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/economia/2020/03/27/sader-delimita-acciones-para-garantizar-abasto-de-alimentos-6457.html Sader delimita acciones para garantizar abasto de alimentos] {{in lang|es}} by  Carolina G\u00f3mez Mena, La Jornada, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n*March 28\n**[[Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell Ram\u00edrez]], Deputy Secretary of Health, said that with 16 deaths and 848 cases of infection, this is the last opportunity to prevent accelerated growth of COVID-19. He called on the population to act responsibly to prevent its spread.<ref>[https://aristeguinoticias.com/2803/mexico/ultima-oportunidad-de-evitar-crecimiento-acelerado-de-covid-19-lopez-gatell-van-16-muertes-y-848-contagiados/ \u00daltima oportunidad de evitar crecimiento acelerado de COVID-19: L\u00f3pez-Gatell; van 16 muertes y 848 contagiados] {{in lang|es}} Arestegui Noticias, 28 Mar 2020</ref> ''[[Milenio]]'' reported that L\u00f3pez-Gatell said there is a legal basis for the use of force to enforce stay-at-home orders during the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>[https://www.milenio.com/politica/covid-19-fuerza-publica-mantener-gente-casa?fbclid=IwAR04pAvd6BR_KgpwKq1ENodfpqbP7D_-isW2C01gBO09mXE9641H_gc1Pig \u00daltima oportunidad para permanecer en casa: L\u00f3pez Gatell] {{in lang|es}} by Fanny Miranda, Milenio, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n**Health officials, accompanied by a representative of the military and Foreign Secretary [[Marcelo Ebrard]] made a video urging the populace to stay home. AMLO did not appear in that video, but he made a separate one with the same message.<ref>[https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/border-baja-california/story/2020-03-28/in-tijuana-video-address-mexicos-president-toughens-coronavirus-stance In Tijuana video address, Mexico\u2019s president toughens coronavirus stance] {{in lang|en}} By WENDY FRY, The San Diego Union-Tribune, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n*30 March \u2013 A national health emergency was declared in Mexico and stricter measures aimed at containing the spread of the virus were introduced.<ref name=\"30march\" />\n*1 April\n**Beaches throughout the country are closed.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Anuncia-Salud-cierre-de-playas-ante-emergencia-por-COVID-19-20200401-0016.html Anuncia Salud cierre de playas ante emergencia por COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} Notimex/Informador, 1 April 2020</ref>\n**INEGI asked everyone who has not taken part of the 2020 census to contact them via their webpage or by calling them before 15 April.<ref>[https://www.milenio.com/politica/comunidad/coronavirus-inegi-pide-entregar-informacion-internet Inegi pide a ciudadanos censarse por internet antes del 15 de abril] {{in lang|es}} Milenio, 1 April 2020</ref>\n**The [[Governor of Nuevo Le\u00f3n]] ordered a halt to production and distribution of beer in the state, beginning April 3.<ref>[https://www.forbes.com.mx/economia-gobierno-nuevo-leon-anuncia-paro-produccion-distribucion-cerveza-pais/?fbclid=IwAR2zgxuKOiLAUhzQ44bbhpf-I1_S461Doh-QPdobMaMDLvm8ZclmNr9egvU NL government anticipates high production and distribution of alcoholic beverages throughout the country] {{in lang|es}} Forbes Mexico, 1 April 2020</ref>\n*3 April \u2013 AMLO issues a decree to abolish 100 public trusts related to science and culture; the [[Secretariat of Finance and Public Credit|Fianance Ministry (SHCP) will receive the money directly.<ref>[https://www.la-prensa.com.mx/mexico/politica/amlo-emite-decreto-para-extincion-de-fideicomisos-publicos-5053897.html AMLO issues decree for the extinction of public trusts] {{in lang|es}} by Carlos Lara, El Sol de M\u00e9xico, 3 Apr 2020</ref> The move is expected to MXN save $250 billion (US $10 billion) which can be spent to strengthen the economy, pay for social programs and pay off the debt.<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/finanzas/con-extincion-de-fideicomisos-se-ahorraran-250-mil-mdp-amlo-5054241.html With extinction of trusts 250 thousand mp will be saved: AMLO] {{in lang|es}} by Sarahi Uribe, El Sol de M\u00e9xico, 3 Apr 2020</ref>\n*Claudia Sheinbaum promised to donate two months of her salary (a total of MXN $156,728) to the struggle against COVID-19 and invited other officials to do so also.<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/metropoli/cdmx/sheinbaum-donara-dos-meses-de-su-salario-para-enfrentar-covid-19-5058851.html Sheinbaum donar\u00e1 dos meses de su salario para enfrentar Covid-19] {{in lang|es}} by Israel Zamarr\u00f3n, El Sol de M\u00e9xico, 4 Apr 2020</ref>\n\n==Cancellations, suspensions, and closings==\n{{Main|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n\n;Archaeological sites\nTeotihuac\u00e1n, Xochicalco, El Tepozteco closed 21\u201322 March. Chich\u00e9n Itz\u00e1 closed indefinitely starting 21 March.<ref name=inah />\n;Educational institutions\n:'''Basic education'''The SEP announced on 14 March that all sporting and civic events in schools would be cancelled<ref name=sep /> and that Easter break would be from 20 March to 20 April.<ref name=\"Prevention Easter break in schools\" /> \n:'''Higher education''': The [[National Autonomous University of Mexico|UNAM]] and [[Monterrey Institute of Technology and Higher Education|Tec de Monterrey]], switched to virtual classes on 13 March.<ref name=cancelations /> Autonomous University of the State of Morelos, (UAEM) suspended classes on 16 March.<ref name=uaem /> Autonomous University of Nuevo Leon, (UANL) suspended classes from 17 March to 20 April.<ref name=uanl /> Autonomous University of Guerrero (UAGRO) and Technical Institute of Guerrero ([[Chilpancingo]]) closed 18 March.<ref name=look />\n;Entertainment\n[[Grupo CIE|OCESA]] cancelled all its events until April 19.<ref name=ocesa>{{cite web|website=El Universal|language=es|trans-title=Ocesa suspends all its events until April 19 due to the coronavirus|title=Ocesa suspende todos sus eventos hasta el 19 de abril por el coronavirus |date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/musica/ocesa-suspende-sus-eventos-hasta-el-19-de-abril-por-el-coronavirus}}</ref>\n:'''Fairs''': Authorities announced on 14 March they were considering the cancellation of the ''Festival Internacional de Cine de Guadalajara''. In M\u00e9rida, the ''Tianguis Tur\u00edstico'' was postponed to September.<ref name=cancelations /> \n:'''Musical''': ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'' suspended until 17 April<ref name=ocesa />\n:'''Concerts''': [[The Magic Numbers]], [[Los Tigres del Norte]], Red Orange County {{sic}}, [[Mercury Rev]], Mar\u00eda Le\u00f3n, [[Sasha Sloan]]<ref name=ocesa /> and [[Ricky Martin]]<ref>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/musica/coronavirus-ricky-martin-cancela-conciertos-en-mexico Ricky Martin cancels all his concerts in Mexico due to coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} El Universal, 13 Mar 2020</ref>\n:'''Conference''': [[Michelle Obama]]<ref name=ocesa />\n:'''Other''': Bars, nightclubs, movie theaters, and museums were closed in Mexico City on 22 March.<ref name=bars />\n;Government\nPresident L\u00f3pez Obrador suspended non-essential activities from 26 March to 19 April. The health and energy sectors, the oil industry, and public services such as water supply, waste management and public safety continued to function.<ref name=suspend_govt />\n;Industry\nFord Motor Company, Honda and Audi closed their manufacturing plants in Mexico on 18 March.<ref name=ford /> Hundreds of hotel employees in [[Canc\u00fan]] were fired.<ref name=cancun /> Alsea ([[Starbucks]], VIPS, [[Domino's Pizza]], [[Burger King]], Italianni's, [[Chili's]], [[California Pizza Kitchen]], [[P. F. Chang's China Bistro]] and [[The Cheesecake Factory]]) offered its employees unpaid leave.<ref name=alsea /> PROFECO closed two businesses in Tijuana Baja California, for price-gouging on 25 March.<ref name=profecobc /> [[Cin\u00e9polis]] announced that they will temporaily close all of their theaters starting March 25.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cin\u00e9polis regresar\u00e1 el dinero de boletos programados |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/cine/cinepolis-regresara-el-dinero-de-boletos-programados|website=El Universal|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|language=es}}</ref>\n;Ports of entry\n:'''Air''': Governor Alfaro Ram\u00edrez of Jalisco announced that beginning Thursday, 26 March, eight states in the [[Baj\u00edo]] and western Mexico woud block flights from areas that had a high rate of coronavirus. The restrictions would apply at the [[Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla Guadalajara International Airport]] and the [[Licenciado Gustavo D\u00edaz Ordaz International Airport]] in Puerto Vallarta.<ref name=planes />\n:'''Land''': The [[United States Department of State]] announced on 20 March there would be restrictions on travel across the Mexico\u2013United States border. The restrictions would not apply to cargo.<ref name=pompeo /> On 26 March, protesters in Sonora insisted that the government limit [[Mexico\u2013United States border|border crossings]] with the United States.<ref name=border /> Chihuahua (state) announced that it would start to quarantine migrants who are returned to the Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez border crossing.<ref name=chi /> Citizens of Nogales, Sonora, blocked border crossing from Nogales, Arizona, in order to prevent the entrance of individuals with the virus infection and to prevent shortages of food, bottled water, toilet paper and cleaning supplies in local stores.<ref name=nogales />\n:'''Sea''': The government announced on 25 March it would continue receiving cruise ships but that passengers would be individually \"fumigated\" before being taken directly to airports to be returned to their home countries.<ref name=sea />\n;Sports\n[[Jalisco Open]] (tennis tournament) and [[CONCACAF Champions League]] (soccer) cancelled 13 March<ref name=cancelations />\n;Religious events\nOn 17 March, [[Passion Play of Iztapalapa]] in Mexico City moved to an undisclosed location indoors and televised on April 10.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[La Jornada]]|title=Suspenden Viacrucis de Iztapalapa; actos a puerta cerrada y v\u00eda tv |language=es|trans-title=Way of the Cross of Iztapalapa suspended; acts behind closed doors and via tv|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020 |url=https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/capital/2020/03/17/cancelan-viacrucis-de-iztapalapa-5742.html}}</ref>\n\nSan Luis Potosi suspended wakes and funerals on March 29.<ref name=funeral />\n;Curfew established\nMayor Juanita Romero ([[National Action Party (Mexico)|PAN]]) of Nacozari de Garc\u00eda, Sonora, declared a curfew in effect until 20 April.<ref name=curfew />\n\n== Notable Mexicans with COVID-19 ==\n{{Div col}}\n*Alejandra Ag\u00fcayo, newscaster ([[FOROtv]])<ref name=famous>[https://www.infobae.com/america/entretenimiento/2020/03/27/famosos-mexicanos-con-coronavirus-y-como-enfrentan-su-aislamiento/ Famous Mexicans with coronaviruses and how they face their isolation] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Jorge Alcib\u00edades Garcia, [[Chamber of Deputies (Mexico)|federal deputy]]<ref name=mil />\n*[[Esteban Arce]], newscaster (''Expreso de la ma\u00f1ana'')<ref name=famous />\n*Mariana Arceo, Mexican [[Pentathlon|pentathelete]] ([[Mexico at the 2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Olympic Team]])<ref name=mil>[https://www.milenio.com/espectaculos/coronavirus-politicos-famosos-y-deportistas-que-han-dado-positivo Athletes, politicians and celebrities who have tested positive for coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} Milenio, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Juan Domingo Beckmann, businessperson ([[Jose Cuervo]] tequila)<ref name=placido />\n*[[Patricio Borghetti]], television presenter (''Venga la Alegr\u00eda''; TV Azteca)<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/entretenimiento/2020/03/26/nada-que-un-taco-no-solucione-otro-dia-en-la-cuarentena-por-coronavirus-de-odalys-ramirez-y-patricio-borghetti/ \"Nothing that a taco does not solve\": another day in the quarantine for coronavirus of Odalys Ram\u00edrez and Patricio Borghetti] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n*[[Placido Domingo]], 79, Spanish tenor who lives in Mexico<ref name=placido>[https://www.lavanguardia.com/musica/20200328/48130404682/placido-domingo-coronavirus.html Pl\u00e1cido Domingo, admitted to Acapulco for complications associated with Covid-19] {{in lang|es}} La Vanguardia, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n*[[Francisco Dom\u00ednguez Servi\u00e9n]], [[Governor of Quer\u00e9taro]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.radioformula.com.mx/noticias/20200330/francisco-dominguez-servien-coronavirus-covid-19-gobernador-queretaro-mexico/|date=30 March 2020|title=Gobernador de Quer\u00e9taro da positivo en coronavirus|agency=radioformula|author=Itzel Garc\u00eda}} {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n*[[Omar Fayad]], [[List of Governors of Hidalgo|Governor of Hidalgo]]<ref>[https://politica.expansion.mx/estados/2020/03/28/el-gobernador-de-hidalgo-omar-fayad-esta-enfermo-de-coronavirus-amlo-mananera-covid-19 The Governor of Hidalgo, Omar Fayad, is sick with coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} Expansi\u00f3n Politica, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Horacio Franco, flautist and director (''Capella Varroca M\u00e9xico'')<ref name=famous />\n*Mar\u00eda Fritz Sierra, General Secretary of the government of [[Yucatan]]<ref>https://www.milenio.com/politica/coronavirus-mexico-31-marzo-casos-noticias-hora-vivo Secretary General of the Yucatan government tests positive for COVID-19] Milenio, 31 Mar 2020</ref>{{better source|date=April 2020}}\n*[[Danna Garc\u00eda]], Colombian actress who resides in Mexico (''El Se\u00f1or de los Cielos'')<ref>[https://www.infobae.com/america/entretenimiento/2020/03/16/danna-garcia-dio-positivo-a-coronavirus-se-mantiene-en-aislamiento-pero-optimista/ Danna Garc\u00eda tested positive for coronavirus: remains in isolation, but optimistic] {{in lang|es}} Infobae, 16 Mar 2020, retrieved 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Mar\u00eda Libier Gonz\u00e1lez Anaya, federal deputy<ref name=dep />\n*[[Jolette (singer)|Jolette]], singer, television presenter, and reality star (''[[La Academia]]'' 2005)<ref name=razon>[https://www.razon.com.mx/entretenimiento/ellos-son-los-famosos-en-mexico-que-se-han-infectado-de-covid-19/ These are the famous Mexicans who have been infected with COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} La Raz\u00f3n, 27 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Jos\u00e9 Kuri Harfush, businessperson ([[Inbursa]])<ref name=univision />\n*Hilde Lara, singer with Yndio<ref name=famous /> \n*[[Ad\u00e1n Augusto L\u00f3pez Hern\u00e1ndez]], [[Governor of Tabasco]]<ref name=loppez_hernandez />\n*Alberto Marrero, businessperson (CEO [[Atl\u00e9tico San Luis]])<ref name=mil />\n*Audomaro P\u00e9rez, 72, bass player ([[Yndio]])<ref name=famous />\n*Mar\u00eda de Jes\u00fas Rosete S\u00e1nchez, federal deputy<ref name=dep>[https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/legisladora-del-pes-da-positivo-de-covid-19-ya-son-3-diputados/ar-BB11T7rR PES legislator tests positive for Covid-19; now there are 3 deputies] {{in lang|es}} La Jornada, 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Jaime Ruiz Sacrist\u00e1n, businessperson (CEO [[Mexican Stock Exchange]])<ref name=univision>[https://www.univision.com/radio/radio-nacional/el-covid-19-no-perdona-camila-sodi-y-otros-famosos-mexicanos-afectados-por-el-coronavirus-fotos \ud83d\udcf8 COVID-19 does not forgive: Camila Sodi and other famous Mexicans affected by the coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} by Constaninos Papilias, Univision, 20 Mar 2020, retrieved 29 Mar 2020</ref>\n*Odalys Ram\u00edrez, television presenter and model (''\u00a1Cu\u00e9ntamelo ya!'' and ''Al aire''; Televisa)<ref name=famous />\n*[[Camila Sodi]], 33, singer and actress<ref name=famous />\n{{End div col}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in Mexico]]\n*[[2020s]]\n*[[Fourth Transformation]]\n*[[History of smallpox in Mexico]]\n*[[Cocoliztli epidemics]]\n*[[Spanish flu|1918 Spanish flu pandemic]]\n*[[2009 flu pandemic in Mexico]]\n*[[HIV/AIDS in Latin America]]\n*[[Dengue fever outbreaks]]\n*[[Epidemiology of chikungunya|2014 chikungunya outbreak in Mexico]]\n*[[2015\u20132016 Zika virus epidemic]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Mexico]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America|Mexico]]\n[[Category:2020 in Mexico|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCancellations, suspensions, and closings:added period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Mexico"}
{"title_page": "Morrison Hotel (Chicago)", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n|name               = Morrison Hotel\n|status             = demolished\n|image              = Morrison Hotel Postcard.jpg\n|image_size         = 250px\n|caption            = 20th century postcard of the Morrison Hotel.\n|location           = 15\u201329 South Clark Street<br/>[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|41.8816|-87.6301|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|start_date         = \n|completion_date    = 1925\n| demolition_date = 1965\n|architect          = [[Holabird & Roche]]\n|owner              = \n|cost               = \n|floor_area         = \n|top_floor          = \n|floor_count        = 45\n|embedded           = \n|references         = <ref name=Emporis>{{emporis|102669}}</ref>\n|building_type      = hotel\n|antenna_spire      = \n|roof               = {{convert|526.1|ft|m}}\n|elevator_count     = \n|structural_engineer= \n|main_contractor    = \n|opening            = \n|developer          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Morrison Hotel''' was a [[high rise]] [[hotel]] at the corner of Madison and Clark Streets in the [[downtown]] [[Chicago Loop|Loop]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States]]. It was designed by the architectural firm of [[Holabird & Roche]] and completed in 1925. The hotel was demolished in 1965 to make room for the [[Chase Tower (Chicago)|First National Bank Building]] (now Chase Tower).\n\nThe hotel was named for Orsemus Morrison, the first [[coroner]] in Chicago, who bought the site in 1838 and in 1860 built a three-story hotel with 21 rooms. Destroyed in the [[Great Chicago Fire]] of 1871, this was replaced by an eight-story building. In 1915 Harry C. Moir, who had bought the property from Morrison's nephew, built a 21-floor, 500-room hotel designed by [[Marshall and Fox]]. The hotel was expanded by 650 rooms in 1918. In 1925 Holabird & Roche further expanded it, adding a 46-story tower. The hotel had 1,800 rooms in 1931. A fourth, 21-story section was then added, bringing the number of rooms to 2,210, but was sold in 1937, becoming the Hotel Chicagoan; in the 1950s this was operated under lease by the Morrison. In 1952 a syndicate bought the Morrison and renovated it.<ref name=UPI>[[United Press International|UPI]]. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19641113&id=s1lWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XkMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5205,6835668&hl=en \"Midwestern Landmark To Vanish: Morrison Hotel In Chicago Ends Colorful History\"]. ''[[Reading Eagle]]''. November 13, 1964. p.&nbsp;17.</ref><ref>William R. Host and Brooke Ahne Portmann. ''Early Chicago Hotels''. Charleston, South Carolina: Arcadia, 2006. {{ISBN|9780738540412}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=pA4NjLaQHcoC&pg=PA50&dq=Morrison+Hotel+Chicago&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifh_Hv5pjLAhUJ9GMKHW7pCysQ6AEIWDAI#v=onepage&q=Morrison%20Hotel%20Chicago&f=false pp.&nbsp;50\u201351].</ref><ref name=AP>[[Associated Press|AP]]. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2202&dat=19650504&id=ekwmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Mv4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=736,4501437&hl=en \"Chicago's Morrison Hotel Being Razed; Was Mecca For Famous Entertainers\"]. ''[[The Gettysburg Times]]''. May 6, 1965. p.&nbsp;4.</ref>\n\nThe 1873 Morrison Hotel housed the Boston Oyster House in its basement.<ref name=AP/> In the skyscraper hotel, the Terrace Casino opened in 1936 with a performance by [[Sophie Tucker]] and was an important [[Big Band]] venue; the Carousel in the Sky was the world's highest nightclub; the Jockey Club on the first floor was the site of protests by the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]] that forced removal of its black [[jockey statue]]s. Presidents [[Harry S. Truman|Truman]], [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]], and [[John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]] and Vice-Presidents [[Alben Barkley|Barkley]] and [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]] stayed at the hotel;<ref name=UPI/> boxer [[Jack Dempsey]] was also a frequent guest. [[Gorgeous George]] was a daily client of the beauty parlor. From 1932 on, the headquarters of the [[Cook County Democratic Party|Cook County Democratic machine]] was on the third floor of the Morrison.<ref name=UPI/><ref name=AP/> Joe \"Hold 'Em\" Powers spent a world record 16 days [[Flagpole sitting|on the hotel flagpole]] in 1927, despite losing six teeth when wind blew him into cables.<ref name=UPI/><ref name=AP/>\n\nIn 1931, the [[Air Line Pilots Association]] was founded in the hotel's ballroom.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hopkins |first1=George E. |title=\"Flying the Lines\" |date=1982 |publisher=Air Line Pilots Association, Int\u2019l |location=Washington, DC |isbn=0-9609708-1-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/flyinglinefirsth00hopk_0/page/9 9] |edition=1st |url=https://archive.org/details/flyinglinefirsth00hopk_0/page/9 |accessdate=4 January 2019 |url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nIn June of 1937, the hotel served as the location in which the Chicago Herald-Examiner kept the notorious murderer, [[Robert George Irwin|Robert Irwin]], sequestered while negotiating terms of his surrender to authorities in Manhattan.<ref>The Mad Sculptor, Harold Schechter (c) 2014 New Harvest, p.248</ref>\n\nOf the Morrison Hotel Chicago were, Mr. William H. Rubin, President of the Morrison Hotel Corporation. Appointed in 1955 were: Mr. John B. Grande, General Manager, Mr. Donald Vescelius Resident Manager, Mr. John Pisa as Front Desk Manager.\n\nMr. Joseph Meyers was Chief Engineer of the Morrison Hotel Chicago, Mr. Joseph Walsh was Assistant Chief Engineer, both were members of Operating Engineers Local 399 Chicago.\n\nStanding {{convert|526|ft|m}} high, the Morrison Hotel was the first building outside of [[New York City]] to have more than 40 floors,<ref name=Emporis/> and for thirty years was the world's tallest hotel.<ref name=UPI/> At the time of its razing in 1965, it was the tallest building to have ever been demolished anywhere in the world.<ref name=Emporis/><ref name=UPI/>\n\n==See Also==\n* [[List of tallest voluntarily demolished buildings]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Chicago}}\n\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Demolished hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Former skyscrapers]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1965]]\n[[Category:Demolished hotels in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n|name               = Morrison Hotel\n|status             = demolished\n|image              = Morrison Hotel Postcard.jpg\n|image_size         = 250px\n|caption            = 20th century postcard of the Morrison Hotel.\n|location           = 15\u201329 South Clark Street<br/>[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|41.8816|-87.6301|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n|start_date         = \n|completion_date    = 1925\n| demolition_date = 1965\n|architect          = [[Holabird & Roche]]\n|owner              = \n|cost               = \n|floor_area         = \n|top_floor          = \n|floor_count        = 45\n|embedded           = \n|references         = <ref name=Emporis>{{emporis|102669}}</ref>\n|building_type      = hotel\n|antenna_spire      = \n|roof               = {{convert|526.1|ft|m}}\n|elevator_count     = \n|structural_engineer= \n|main_contractor    = \n|opening            = \n|developer          = \n}}\n\nThe '''Morrison Hotel''' was a [[high rise]] [[hotel]] at the corner of Madison and Clark Streets in the [[downtown]] [[Chicago Loop|Loop]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community area]] of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], [[United States]]. It was designed by the architectural firm of [[Holabird & Roche]] and completed in 1925. The hotel was demolished in 1965 to make room for the [[Chase Tower (Chicago)|First National Bank Building]] (now Chase Tower).\n\nThe hotel was named for Orsemus Morrison, the first [[coroner]] in Chicago, who bought the site in 1838 and in 1860 built a three-story hotel with 21 rooms. Destroyed in the [[Great Chicago Fire]] of 1871, this was replaced by an eight-story building. In 1915 Harry C. Moir, who had bought the property from Morrison's nephew, built a 21-floor, 500-room hotel designed by [[Marshall and Fox]]. The hotel was expanded by 650 rooms in 1918. In 1925 Holabird & Roche further expanded it, adding a 46-story tower. The hotel had 1,800 rooms in 1931. A fourth, 21-story section was then added, bringing the number of rooms to 2,210, but was sold in 1937, becoming the Hotel Chicagoan; in the 1950s this was operated under lease by the Morrison. In 1952 a syndicate bought the Morrison and renovated it.<ref name=UPI>[[United Press International|UPI]]. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1955&dat=19641113&id=s1lWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XkMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5205,6835668&hl=en \"Midwestern Landmark To Vanish: Morrison Hotel In Chicago Ends Colorful History\"]. ''[[Reading Eagle]]''. November 13, 1964. p.&nbsp;17.</ref><ref>William R. Host and Brooke Ahne Portmann. ''Early Chicago Hotels''. Charleston, South Carolina: Arcadia, 2006. {{ISBN|9780738540412}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=pA4NjLaQHcoC&pg=PA50&dq=Morrison+Hotel+Chicago&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwifh_Hv5pjLAhUJ9GMKHW7pCysQ6AEIWDAI#v=onepage&q=Morrison%20Hotel%20Chicago&f=false pp.&nbsp;50\u201351].</ref><ref name=AP>[[Associated Press|AP]]. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2202&dat=19650504&id=ekwmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Mv4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=736,4501437&hl=en \"Chicago's Morrison Hotel Being Razed; Was Mecca For Famous Entertainers\"]. ''[[The Gettysburg Times]]''. May 6, 1965. p.&nbsp;4.</ref>\n\nThe 1873 Morrison Hotel housed the Boston Oyster House in its basement.<ref name=AP/> In the skyscraper hotel, the Terrace Casino opened in 1936 with a performance by [[Sophie Tucker]] and was an important [[Big Band]] venue; the Carousel in the Sky was the world's highest nightclub; the Jockey Club on the first floor was the site of protests by the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People]] that forced removal of its black [[jockey statue]]s. Presidents [[Harry S. Truman|Truman]], [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|Eisenhower]], and [[John F. Kennedy|Kennedy]] and Vice-Presidents [[Alben Barkley|Barkley]] and [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]] stayed at the hotel;<ref name=UPI/> boxer [[Jack Dempsey]] was also a frequent guest. [[Gorgeous George]] was a daily client of the beauty parlor. From 1932 on, the headquarters of the [[Cook County Democratic Party|Cook County Democratic machine]] was on the third floor of the Morrison.<ref name=UPI/><ref name=AP/> Joe \"Hold 'Em\" Powers spent a world record 16 days [[Flagpole sitting|on the hotel flagpole]] in 1927, despite losing six teeth when wind blew him into cables.<ref name=UPI/><ref name=AP/>\n\nIn 1931, the [[Air Line Pilots Association]] was founded in the hotel's ballroom.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hopkins |first1=George E. |title=\"Flying the Lines\" |date=1982 |publisher=Air Line Pilots Association, Int\u2019l |location=Washington, DC |isbn=0-9609708-1-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/flyinglinefirsth00hopk_0/page/9 9] |edition=1st |url=https://archive.org/details/flyinglinefirsth00hopk_0/page/9 |accessdate=4 January 2019 |url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nIn June of 1937, the hotel served as the location in which the Chicago Herald-Examiner kept the notorious murderer, Robert Irwin, sequestered while negotiating terms of his surrender to authorities in Manhattan.<ref>The Mad Sculptor, Harold Schechter (c) 2014 New Harvest, p.248</ref>\n\nOf the Morrison Hotel Chicago were, Mr. William H. Rubin, President of the Morrison Hotel Corporation. Appointed in 1955 were: Mr. John B. Grande, General Manager, Mr. Donald Vescelius Resident Manager, Mr. John Pisa as Front Desk Manager.\n\nMr. Joseph Meyers was Chief Engineer of the Morrison Hotel Chicago, Mr. Joseph Walsh was Assistant Chief Engineer, both were members of Operating Engineers Local 399 Chicago.\n\nStanding {{convert|526|ft|m}} high, the Morrison Hotel was the first building outside of [[New York City]] to have more than 40 floors,<ref name=Emporis/> and for thirty years was the world's tallest hotel.<ref name=UPI/> At the time of its razing in 1965, it was the tallest building to have ever been demolished anywhere in the world.<ref name=Emporis/><ref name=UPI/>\n\n==See Also==\n* [[List of tallest voluntarily demolished buildings]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Chicago}}\n\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Demolished hotels in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Former skyscrapers]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1965]]\n[[Category:Demolished hotels in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Herostratus", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morrison_Hotel_(Chicago)"}
{"title_page": "Arcturus", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{short description|Star in the constellation Bo\u00f6tes}}\n{{Starbox begin\n | name=Arcturus\n}}\n{{Starbox image\n| image = \n     <div style=\"position: relative\">[[File:Bo\u00f6tes IAU.svg|250px|alt=Diagram showing star positions and boundaries of the Bo\u00f6tes constellation and its surroundings]]\n     <div style=\"position: absolute; left: 53.6%; top: 59.6%\">[[File:Cercle rouge 100%.svg|12px]]</div>\n     </div>\n| caption=Arcturus in the constellation of Bo\u00f6tes (circled)\n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n | epoch       =J2000\n | constell    =[[Bo\u00f6tes]]\n | pronounce   ={{IPAc-en|\u0251\u02d0r|k|\u02c8|tj|\u028a\u0259r|\u0259|s}}\n | ra          ={{RA|14|15|39.7}}<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/>\n | dec         ={{DEC|+19|10|56}}<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/>\n | appmag_v    =&minus;0.05<ref name=ducati/>\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n | class             = K0 III<ref name=gray>{{cite journal|bibcode=2003AJ....126.2048G|title=Contributions to the Nearby Stars (NStars) Project: Spectroscopy of Stars Earlier than M0 within 40 Parsecs: The Northern Sample. I|journal=The Astronomical Journal|volume=126|issue=4|pages=2048|last1=Gray|first1=R. O.|last2=Corbally|first2=C. J.|last3=Garrison|first3=R. F.|last4=McFadden|first4=M. T.|last5=Robinson|first5=P. E.|date=2003|doi=10.1086/378365|arxiv = astro-ph/0308182 }}</ref>\n | appmag_1_passband = [[J band (infrared)|J]]\n | appmag_1          = &minus;2.25<ref name=ducati>{{cite journal|bibcode=2002yCat.2237....0D|title=VizieR Online Data Catalog: Catalogue of Stellar Photometry in Johnson's 11-color system|journal=CDS/ADC Collection of Electronic Catalogues|volume=2237|pages=0|last1=Ducati|first1=J. R.|date=2002}}</ref>\n | b-v               = +1.23<ref name=ducati/>\n | u-b               = +1.28<ref name=ducati/>\n | r-i               = +0.65<ref name=ducati/>\n | v-r               =\n | variable          =\n}}\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFAFA\"\n| Note (category: variability): || H and K emission vary.\n{{Starbox astrometry\n | radial_v          =\u22125.19<ref>{{cite journal|bibcode=2008AJ....135..209M|title=Rotational and Radial Velocities for a Sample of 761 HIPPARCOS Giants and the Role of Binarity|journal=The Astronomical Journal|volume=135|issue=1|pages=209\u2013231|last1=Massarotti|first1=Alessandro|last2=Latham|first2=David W.|last3=Stefanik|first3=Robert P.|last4=Fogel|first4=Jeffrey|date=2008|doi=10.1088/0004-6256/135/1/209}}</ref>\n | prop_mo_ra        ={{val|-1093.45}}<ref name=\"Perryman1997\">{{cite web|url=http://webviz.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/VizieR-5?-source=I/239/tyc_main&HIP=69673|title=HIP 69673|work=The Hipparcos and Tycho Catalogues|author=Perryman|date=1997|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n | prop_mo_dec       ={{val|-1999.40}}<ref name=\"Perryman1997\" />\n | parallax          =88.83\n | p_error           =0.54\n | parallax_footnote =<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\" />\n | absmag_v          ={{val|-0.30|0.02}}<ref name=aj135_3_892/>\n}}\n{{Starbox detail\n | mass                ={{val|1.08|0.06}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | metal_fe            ={{val|-0.52|0.04}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | radius              ={{val|25.4|0.2}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | rotational_velocity ={{val|2.4|1.0}}<ref name=aj135_3_892/>\n | luminosity          =170<ref name=aaa465_2_593/>\n | temperature         ={{val|4286|30}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | gravity             ={{val|1.66|0.05}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | age_gyr             ={{val|7.1|+1.5|-1.2}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n}}\n{{Starbox catalog\n | names={{odlist | name=Alramech | name2=Alramech | name3=Abramech | B=\u03b1&nbsp;Bo\u00f6tis | F=16 Bo\u00f6tis | BD=+19\u00b0 2777 | GJ=541 | HD=124897 | HIP=69673 | HR=5340 | SAO=100944 | GCTP=3242.00 | LHS=48 }}, [[General Catalogue of Trigonometric Parallaxes|GCTP]]&nbsp;3242.00\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n | Simbad=HD+124897\n | ARICNS =\n}}\n{{starbox sources|HIP|CCDM|HR|[http://webviz.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/VizieR-S?HR%205340 VizieR catalog entry]}}\n{{Starbox end}}\n\n'''Arcturus''', designation '''\u03b1&nbsp;Bo\u00f6tis''' ([[Latinisation of names|Latinized]] to '''Alpha&nbsp;Bo\u00f6tis''', abbreviated '''Alpha&nbsp;Boo''', '''\u03b1&nbsp;Boo'''), is the brightest [[star]] in the [[constellation]] of [[Bo\u00f6tes]], the [[List of brightest stars|fourth-brightest]] in the [[night sky]], and the brightest in the [[northern celestial hemisphere]]. Together with [[Spica]] and [[Denebola]] (or [[Regulus]], depending on the source), Arcturus is part of the [[Spring Triangle]] [[Asterism (astronomy)|asterism]] and, by extension, also of the [[Great Diamond]] along with the star [[Cor Caroli]].\n\nRelatively close at 36.7 [[light-year]]s from the [[Sun]], Arcturus is a [[red giant]] of spectral type K0III\u2014an aging star around 7.1 billion years old that has used up its [[Stellar core|core]] [[hydrogen]] and moved off the [[main sequence]]. It is {{Val|1.08|0.06}} times as massive [[Solar mass|as the Sun]], but has expanded to {{Val|25.4|0.2}} times [[Solar radius|its diameter]] and is around 170 times [[Solar luminosity|as luminous]].\n\n==Nomenclature==\n''\u03b1 Bo\u00f6tis'' ([[Latinisation of names|Latinised]] to ''Alpha Bo\u00f6tis'') is the star's [[Bayer designation]].\n\nThe traditional name ''Arcturus'' derives from [[Ancient Greek]] \u1f08\u03c1\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''Arktouros'') and means \"Guardian of the Bear\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3D*%29arktou%3Dros |title=\u1f08\u03c1\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 |author1=Henry George Liddell |author2=Robert Scott |work=A Greek-English Lexicon| accessdate=2019-01-16}}</ref> ultimately from \u1f04\u03c1\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 (''arktos''), \"bear\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Da%29%2Frktos |title=\u1f04\u03c1\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 |author1=Henry George Liddell |author2=Robert Scott |work=A Greek-English Lexicon| accessdate=2019-01-16}}</ref> and \u03bf\u1f56\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''ouros''), \"watcher, guardian\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dou%29%3Dros2 |title=\u03bf\u1f56\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 |author1=Henry George Liddell |author2=Robert Scott |work=A Greek-English Lexicon| accessdate=2019-01-16}}</ref> It has been known by this name since at least the time of [[Hesiod]].<ref name=rogers982/>\n\n===Mythology===\n{{See also|Ursa Major#Mythology|Bo\u00f6tes#History and mythology}}\nOne astronomical tradition associates Arcturus with the mythology around [[Arcas]], who was about to shoot and kill his own mother [[Callisto (mythology)|Callisto]] who had been transformed into a bear. Zeus averted their imminent tragic fate by transforming the boy into the constellation Bo\u00f6tes, called Arctophylax \"bear guardian\" by the Greeks, and his mother into Ursa Major (Greek: Arctos \"the bear\"). The account is given in [[Gaius Julius Hyginus|Hyginus]]'s ''[[De Astronomica|Astronomy]]''.<ref>{{cite book|ref={{SfnRef|Eratosthenes|Hyginus|Aratus|Hard (tr.)|2015}}|author1=Eratosthenes |author2=Hyginus |author3=Aratus |others=Hard, Robin (transl.) |title=Eratosthenes and Hyginus: Constellation Myths, with Aratus's Phaenomena |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2015 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7IMSBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA36 |pages=5\u20137, 35\u201337|isbn=9780198716983 }}</ref>\n\n[[Aratus]] in his ''Phaenomena'' said that the star Arcturus lay below the belt of Arctophylax, although according to [[Ptolemy]] in the ''Almagest'' it lay between his thighs.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/bootes.htm| author=Ridpath, Ian |title=Star Tales Bo\u00f6tes |accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn alternative lore associates the name with the legend around [[Icarius (Athenian)|Icarius]], who gave the gift of wine to other men, but was murdered by them, because they had had no experience with intoxication and mistook the wine for poison. It is stated this Icarius, became Arcturus, while his dog, [[Maera (hound)|Maira]], became Canicula ([[Procyon]]), although \"Arcturus\" here may be used in the sense of the constellation rather than the star.<ref>{{harvp|Eratosthenes|Hyginus|Aratus|Hard (tr.)|2015|pp=38\u201340}}, p. 182 (note to p. 40)</ref>\n\n===Standardization===\nIn 2016, the [[International Astronomical Union]] organized a [[IAU Working Group on Star Names|Working Group on Star Names]] (WGSN)<ref name=\"WGSN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.iau.org/science/scientific_bodies/working_groups/280/ | title=IAU Working Group on Star Names (WGSN)|accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref> to catalog and standardize proper names for stars. The WGSN's first bulletin of July 2016<ref name=\"WGSN1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/WGSN_bulletin1.pdf | title=Bulletin of the IAU Working Group on Star Names, No. 1 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> included a table of the first two batches of names approved by the WGSN; which included ''Arcturus'' for this star. It is now so entered in the IAU Catalog of Star Names.<ref name=\"IAU-CSN\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/IAU-CSN.txt | title=IAU Catalog of Star Names |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Observation==\n\nWith an [[apparent visual magnitude]] of&nbsp;&minus;0.05, Arcturus is the brightest star in the [[northern celestial hemisphere]] and the [[list of brightest stars|fourth-brightest star]] in the night sky,<ref name=\"100greatest\">{{cite book | title=The Hundred Greatest Stars | author=Kaler, James B. | date=2002 | publisher=Copernicus Books | location=New York, New York | isbn=978-0-387-95436-3 | page=21}}</ref> after [[Sirius]] (&minus;1.46&nbsp;apparent magnitude), [[Canopus (star)|Canopus]] (&minus;0.72) and [[\u03b1 Centauri]] (combined magnitude of &minus;0.27). However, \u03b1 Centauri AB is a [[binary star]], whose components are both fainter than Arcturus. This makes Arcturus the third-brightest individual star, just ahead of \u03b1 Centauri&nbsp;A (officially named ''Rigil Kentaurus''), whose apparent magnitude {{nobr|is &minus;0.01}}.<ref name=schaaf>{{cite book| first=Fred | last=Schaaf | date=2008 | title=The Brightest Stars: Discovering the Universe Through the Sky's Most Brilliant Stars | pages=126\u201336 | publisher=John Wiley and Sons|location=Hoboken, New Jersey | isbn=978-0-471-70410-2 | bibcode=2008bsdu.book.....S }}</ref> The French mathematician and astronomer [[Jean-Baptiste Morin (mathematician)|Jean-Baptiste Morin]] observed Arcturus in the daytime with a telescope in 1635, a first for any star other than the [[Sun]] and [[supernova]]e.  Arcturus has been seen at or just before sunset with the naked eye.<ref name=schaaf/>\n\nArcturus is visible from both of [[Earth]]'s hemispheres as it is located 19\u00b0 north of the [[celestial equator]]. The star [[culmination|culminates]] at midnight on 27 April, and at 9 p.m. on June 10 being visible during the late northern spring or the southern autumn.<ref>Schaaf, p. 257.</ref> From the [[northern hemisphere]], an easy way to find Arcturus is to follow the arc of the handle of the [[Big Dipper]] (or Plough). By continuing in this path, one can find [[Spica]], \"Arc to Arcturus, then spike (or speed on) to Spica\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=Joe |title=Arc to Arcturus, Speed on to Spica |url=https://www.space.com/3953-arc-arcturus-speed-spica.html |accessdate=14 August 2018 |work=Space.com |date=June 15, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Follow the arc to Arcturus, and drive a spike to Spica {{!}} EarthSky.org |url=http://earthsky.org/tonight/follow-the-arc-to-arcturus |accessdate=14 August 2018 |work=earthsky.org |date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPtolemy described Arcturus as ''subrufa'' (\"slightly red\"): it has a B-V color index of +1.23, roughly midway between [[Pollux (star)|Pollux]] (B-V +1.00) and [[Aldebaran]] (B-V +1.54).<ref name=schaaf/>\n\n[[\u03b7 Bo\u00f6tis]], or Muphrid, is only 3.3 [[light-year]]s distant from Arcturus, and would have a visual magnitude \u22122.5, about as bright as [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] from [[Earth]], whereas an observer on the former system would find Arcturus as bright as [[Venus]] as seen from Earth.<ref name=schaaf/>\n\nIn 1984, the 90&nbsp;cm (36-inch) reflecting [[Yapp telescope]] at Herstmonceux was tested with an [[echelle spectrograph]] from [[Queen's University Belfast]] and a CCD camera. Observations of the stars Arcturus and [[Deneb]] (Alpha Cygni) were conducted in the summer of 1984.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite journal |bibcode=1985A&A...145..321B |title=High dispersion spectroscopy trials using an echelle spectrograph with CCD camera |journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics |volume=145 |pages=321 |last1=Bates |first1=B. |last2=McKeith |first2=C. D. |last3=Jorden |first3=P. R. |last4=Van Breda |first4=I. G. |year=1985 }}</ref>\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n[[File:Arcturus (optical).png|thumb|right|275 px|Optical image of Arcturus (DSS2 / MAST / STScI / NASA)]]\nBased upon an annual [[stellar parallax|parallax]] shift of 88.83&nbsp;[[Minute and second of arc#Astronomy|milliarcseconds]] as measured by the [[Hipparcos]] satellite, Arcturus is {{Convert|11.26|pc|ly|abbr=off|lk=on|order=flip}} from the Sun. The parallax [[margin of error]] is 0.54 milliarcseconds, translating to a distance margin of error of \u00b1{{Convert|0.069|pc|ly|abbr=off|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/> Because of its proximity, Arcturus has a high [[proper motion]], two [[Minute and second of arc#Astronomy|arcseconds]] a year, greater than any [[first magnitude star]] other than \u03b1&nbsp;Centauri.\n\nArcturus is moving rapidly ({{nowrap|122 km/s}}) relative to the Sun, and is now almost at its closest point to the Sun. Closest approach will happen in about 4,000 years, when the star will be a few hundredths of a light-year closer to Earth than it is today. (In antiquity, Arcturus was closer to the centre of the constellation.<ref name=rogers982>{{cite journal | last = Rogers | first = John H. | date = 1998 | title = Origins of the Ancient Constellations: II. The Mediterranean Traditions | journal = Journal of the British Astronomical Association | volume = 108 | issue = 2 | pages = 79\u201389 | bibcode = 1998JBAA..108...79R}}</ref>) Arcturus is thought to be an [[old-disk star]], and appears to be moving with a group of 52 other such stars, known as the [[Arcturus stream]].<ref name=ramya>{{cite journal|bibcode=2012MNRAS.425.3188R|arxiv=1207.0767|title=Chemical compositions of stars in two stellar streams from the Galactic thick disc|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=425|issue=4|pages=3188|last1=Ramya|first1=P.|last2=Reddy|first2=Bacham E.|last3=Lambert|first3=David L.|date=2012|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2012.21677.x}}</ref>\n\nWith an [[absolute magnitude]] of \u22120.30, Arcturus is, together with [[Vega]] and Sirius, one of the most luminous stars in the Sun's neighborhood. It is about 110 times brighter than the Sun in visible light wavelengths, but this underestimates its strength as much of the light it gives off is in the [[infrared]]; total ([[Bolometric correction|bolometric]]) power output is about 180&nbsp;times that of the Sun.  With a near-infrared [[J band (infrared)|J band]] [[Magnitude (astronomy)|magnitude]] of \u22122.2, only [[Betelgeuse]] (\u22122.9) and [[R Doradus]] (\u22122.6) are brighter.  The lower output in visible light is due to a lower [[Luminous efficacy|efficacy]] as the star has a lower [[effective temperature|surface temperature]] than the Sun.\n\nArcturus is an [[stellar evolution|evolved]] [[red giant]] star with a [[stellar classification]] of K0&nbsp;III. As the brightest K-type [[Giant star#Red giants|giant]] in the sky, it was the subject of an [[spectral atlas|atlas]] of its visible [[stellar spectrum|spectrum]], made from [[photographic plate|photographic]] spectra taken with the [[Reflecting telescope#Coud\u00e9|coud\u00e9]] [[spectrograph]] of the [[Mount Wilson Observatory|Mt. Wilson 2.5m telescope]] published in 1968,<ref>{{cite book | last=Griffin | first=R. E. |last2=Griffin | first2=R. | title=A photometric atlas of the spectrum of Arcturus, \u03bb\u03bb3600-8825\u00c5 | publisher=Cambridge Philosophical Society |location=Cambridge | date=1968 | bibcode=1968pmas.book.....G }}</ref> a key reference work for stellar spectroscopy. Subsequent spectral atlases<ref>{{cite book | last=Hinkle | first=Kenneth |last2=Wallace | first2=Lloyd | last3=Valenti | first3=Jeff | last4=Harmer | first4=Dianne | title=Visible and Near Infrared Atlas of the Arcturus Spectrum 3727-9300 \u00c5 | bibcode=2000vnia.book.....H | publisher=[[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]] | location=San Francisco | isbn=978-1-58381-037-8 | date=2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Hinkle | first=Kenneth |last2=Wallace | first2=Lloyd | last3=Livingston |first3=William Charles | title=Infrared atlas of the Arcturus spectrum, 0.9-5.3 microns | bibcode=1995iaas.book.....H | publisher=Astronomical Society of the Pacific | location=San Francisco | date=1995 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Hinkle | first=Kenneth |last2=Wallace | first2=Lloyd | last3=Valenti |first3=Jeff | last4=Ayres | first4=Thomas | title=Ultraviolet Atlas of the Arcturus Spectrum, 1150-3800 \u00c5 | bibcode=2005uaas.book.....H | publisher=Astronomical Society of the Pacific | location=San Francisco | date=2005 }}</ref> with greater wavelength coverage and superior [[signal-to-noise ratio]] made with digital detectors have supplanted the older work, but the Arcturus spectrum remains an important standard for stellar spectroscopy.\n\nAs a single star, the mass of Arcturus cannot be measured directly, but models suggest it is slightly larger than that of the Sun. Evolutionary matching to the observed physical parameters gives a mass of {{Val|1.08|0.06|u=solar mass}},<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/> while the oxygen isotope ratio for a first [[dredge-up]] star gives a mass of {{solar mass|1.2}}.<ref name=abia>{{cite journal|bibcode=2012A&A...548A..55A|arxiv=1210.1160|title=Carbon and oxygen isotopic ratios in Arcturus and Aldebaran. Constraining the parameters for non-convective mixing on the red giant branch|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=548|pages=A55|last1=Abia|first1=C.|last2=Palmerini|first2=S.|last3=Busso|first3=M.|last4=Cristallo|first4=S.|date=2012|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201220148}}</ref> The star displays [[Stellar magnetic field|magnetic activity]] that is heating the [[stellar corona|coronal]] structures, and it undergoes a [[Solar cycle|solar-type magnetic cycle]] with a duration that is probably less than 14 years. A weak magnetic field has been detected in the [[photosphere]] with a strength of around half a [[Gauss (unit)|gauss]]. The magnetic activity appears to lie along four latitudes and is rotationally-modulated.<ref name=Sennhauser2011>{{cite journal | title=First detection of a weak magnetic field on the giant Arcturus: remnants of a solar dynamo? | last1=Sennhauser | first1=C. | last2=Berdyugina | first2=S. V. | journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics | volume=529 | id=A100 | pages=6 | date=May 2011 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201015445 | bibcode=2011A&A...529A.100S }}</ref>\n\nArcturus is estimated to be around 6 billion to 8.5 billion years old,<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/> but there is some uncertainty about its evolutionary status.<ref name=Pavlenko2008/> Based upon the [[Color index|color characteristics]] of Arcturus, it is currently ascending the [[red-giant branch]] and will continue to do so until it accumulates a large enough degenerate helium [[Stellar core|core]] to ignite the [[helium flash]].<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/> It has likely exhausted the [[hydrogen]] from its core and is now in its active [[red giant|hydrogen shell burning]] phase. However, Charbonnel et al. (1998) placed it slightly above the [[horizontal branch]], and suggested it has already completed the helium flash stage.<ref name=Pavlenko2008>{{cite journal | title=The carbon abundance and <sup>12</sup>C/<sup>13</sup>C isotopic ratio in the atmosphere of Arcturus from 2.3 \u00b5m CO bands | last1=Pavlenko | first1=Ya. V. | journal=Astronomy Reports | volume=52 | issue=9 | pages=749\u2013759 | date=September 2008 | doi=10.1134/S1063772908090060 | bibcode=2008ARep...52..749P | arxiv=0807.3667 }}</ref>\n\n===Oscillations===\nAs one of the brightest stars in the sky, Arcturus has been the subject of a number of studies in the emerging field of [[asteroseismology]]. Belmonte and colleagues carried out a radial velocity (Doppler shift of spectral lines) study of the star in April and May 1988, which showed variability with a frequency of the order of a few micro[[hertz]] (\u03bcHz), the highest peak corresponding to 4.3&nbsp;\u03bcHz (2.7&nbsp;days) with an amplitude of 60 ms<sup>\u22121</sup>, with a [[frequency separation]] of c.&nbsp;5&nbsp;\u03bcHz. They suggested that the most plausible explanation for the variability of Arcturus is stellar oscillations.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Belmonte, J. A.|author2=Jones, A. R.|author3=Palle, P. L.|author4=Roca Cortes, T.|date=1990|title=Acoustic oscillations in the K2 III star Arcturus|journal=Astrophysics and Space Science|volume=169|issue=1\u20132|pages=77\u201384|issn=0004-640X|doi=10.1007/BF00640689 |bibcode=1990Ap&SS.169...77B}}</ref>\n\nAsteroseismological measurements allow direct calculation of the mass and radius, giving values of {{Val|0.8|0.2|u=solar mass}} and {{Val|27.9|3.4|ul=solar radius}}. This form of modelling is still relatively inaccurate, but a useful check on other models.<ref name=kallinger>{{cite journal|bibcode=2010A&A...509A..77K|title=Oscillating red giants in the CoRoT exofield: Asteroseismic mass and radius determination|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=509|pages=A77|last1=Kallinger|first1=T.|last2=Weiss|first2=W. W.|last3=Barban|first3=C.|last4=Baudin|first4=F.|last5=Cameron|first5=C.|last6=Carrier|first6=F.|last7=De Ridder|first7=J.|last8=Goupil|first8=M.-J.|last9=Gruberbauer|first9=M.|last10=Hatzes|first10=A.|last11=Hekker|first11=S.|last12=Samadi|first12=R.|last13=Deleuil|first13=M.|date=2010|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/200811437|arxiv=0811.4674}}</ref>\n\n===Element abundance===\nAstronomers term \"metals\" those elements with higher [[atomic number]]s than [[helium]]. Arcturus has an enrichment of [[alpha elements]] relative to [[iron]] but only about a third of solar [[metallicity]]. Arcturus is possibly a [[Population II star]].<ref name=schaaf/>\n\n===Possible planetary system===\n''Hipparcos'' also suggested that Arcturus is a [[binary star]], with the companion about twenty times dimmer than the primary and orbiting close enough to be at the very limits of humans' current ability to make it out. Recent results remain inconclusive, but do support the marginal ''Hipparcos'' detection of a binary companion.<ref>{{Cite journal| first1=T.|last1=Verhoelst|first2=P. J.|display-authors= 4|last2= Bord\u00e9|first3=G.|last3=Perrin|first4=L.|last4=Decin|title=Is Arcturus a well-understood K giant?|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|date=2005|volume=435|pages=289\u2013301|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20042356|last5= Eriksson|first5=K.|last6=Ridgway|first6=S. T.|last7=Schuller|first7=P. A.|last8=Traub|first8=W. A.|last9=Millan-Gabet|first9=R.|last10=Lacasse|first10=M. G.|last11=Waelkens|first11=C.|  postscript=<!--None-->|bibcode=2005A&A...435..289V|arxiv=astro-ph/0501669}}, and see references therein.</ref>\n\nIn 1993, radial velocity measurements of Aldebaran, Arcturus and Pollux showed that Arcturus exhibited a long-period radial velocity oscillation, which could be interpreted as a ''substellar companion''. This [[substellar object]] would be nearly 12&nbsp;times the [[mass of Jupiter]] and be located roughly at the same orbital distance from Arcturus as the Earth is from the Sun, at 1.1&nbsp;[[astronomical unit]]s. However, all three stars surveyed showed similar oscillations yielding similar companion masses, and the authors concluded that the variation was likely to be intrinsic to the star rather than due to the gravitational effect of a companion. So far no substellar companion has been confirmed.<ref name=Kgiants>{{cite journal|doi=10.1086/173002|title=Long-period radial velocity variations in three K giants|author=Hatzes, A.|author2=Cochran, W.|journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]]|volume=413|issue = 1|pages=339\u2013348|date=August 1993|bibcode=1993ApJ...413..339H}}</ref>\n<!--\n{{PlanetboxOrbit begin}}\n{{PlanetboxOrbit hypothetical\n| exoplanet = [[Arcturus b|b]]\n| mass = 11.7\n| period = 233\n| semimajor = 1.1\n| eccentricity = 0.147\n}}\n{{PlanetboxOrbit end}}\nPut the starbox in once a planet has been confirmed, if it is a planet and not a brown dwarf.-->\n\n==Other names==\n\n=== In Arabic ===\nIn [[Arabic]], Arcturus is one of two stars called ''al-sim\u0101k'' \"the uplifted ones\" (the other is [[Spica]]). Arcturus is specified as \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0645\u062d ''as-sim\u0101k ar-r\u0101mi\u0127'' \"the uplifted one of the lancer\". The term ''Al Simak Al Ramih'' has appeared in Al Achsasi Al Mouakket catalogue (translated into [[Latin]] as ''Al Simak Lanceator'').<ref>{{cite journal|last=Knobel|first=E. B.|title=Al Achsasi Al Mouakket, on a catalogue of stars in the Calendarium of Mohammad Al Achsasi Al Mouakket|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=55|issue=8|page=429|date=June 1895|bibcode= 1895MNRAS..55..429K|doi=10.1093/mnras/55.8.429}}</ref>\n\nThis has been variously [[Romanization|romanized]] in the past, leading to obsolete variants such as ''Aramec'' and ''Azimech''. For example, the name ''Alramih'' is used in [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[A Treatise on the Astrolabe]]'' (1391). Another Arabic name is ''Haris-el-sema'', from ''\u062d\u0627\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0621'' ''\u0127\u0101ris al-sam\u0101\u2019'' \"the keeper of heaven\".<ref name=arabicstar>{{cite web|url=http://www.jas.org.jo/arabic/alma.html|title= List of the 25&nbsp;brightest stars|website = Jordanian Astronomical Society|accessdate=March 28, 2007}}</ref><ref name=allen>{{cite book|author=Allen, Richard Hinckley |title=Star-names and their meanings|date=1936|pages= 100\u2013101}}</ref><ref name=arabicdict>{{cite book|author=Wehr, Hans |editor=Cowan, J. Milton |title=A dictionary of modern written Arabic|date=1994}}</ref> or ''\u062d\u0627\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0644'' ''\u0127\u0101ris al-sham\u0101l\u2019'' \"the keeper of north\".<ref>{{cite journal|author=Davis Jr., G. A.|bibcode=1944PA.....52....8D |title=The Pronunciations, Derivations, and Meanings of a Selected List of Star Names|journal=Popular Astronomy|volume= 52|date=  October 3, 1944|page= 13}}</ref>\n\nArcturus was once again called by its classical name from the Renaissance onwards.<ref>{{cite book |author= Kunitzsch, Paul |author2= Smart, Tim|date = 2006|title = A Dictionary of Modern star Names: A Short Guide to 254 Star Names and Their Derivations |edition = 2nd rev.  |publisher = [[Sky Publishing Corporation|Sky Pub]] |location = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts|MA]] |isbn = 978-1-931559-44-7 |page = 19}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nIn [[Chinese astronomy]], Arcturus is called ''Da Jiao'' ({{zh|c=\u5927\u89d2|p=D\u00e0ji\u01ceo|l=great horn}}), because it is the brightest star in the [[Chinese constellation]] called ''[[Horn (Chinese constellation)|Jiao Xiu]]'' ({{zh|c=\u89d2\u5bbf|p=Ji\u01ceo Xi\u01d4|l=horn star|links=no}}). Later it became a part of another constellation ''[[Neck (Chinese constellation)|Kang Xiu]]'' ({{zh|c=\u4ea2\u5bbf|p=K\u00e0ng Xi\u01d4|links=no}}).\n\nIn Indian [[Astrology]] or [[Hindu astrology|Vedic Astrology]] or [[Sidereal Astrology]], Arcturus is called ''[[Swati the Star|Swati]]'' which is a word meaning \"very beneficent\" derived from the language [[Sanskrit]]. It is the [[eponymous]] star of one of the [[nakshatra]]s (lunar mansions) of [[Hindu astrology]].\n\n===Other languages===\nThe [[Wotjobaluk people|Wotjobaluk]] [[Koori]] people of southeastern Australia knew Arcturus as ''Marpean-kurrk'', mother of ''Djuit'' ([[Antares]]) and another star in Bo\u00f6tes, ''Weet-kurrk''<ref name=mud>{{Cite book|last=Mudrooroo|title=Aboriginal mythology : an A-Z spanning the history of aboriginal mythology from the earliest legends to the present day|publisher=HarperCollins|location=London|date= 1994|page=5|isbn=978-1-85538-306-7}}</ref> (Muphrid).<ref name=hamacher10>{{cite journal|author=Hamacher, Duane W.|author2=Frew, David J. |date=2010|title= An Aboriginal Australian Record of the Great Eruption of Eta Carinae|journal=Journal of Astronomical History & Heritage |volume=13|issue=3|pages= 220\u201334|arxiv = 1010.4610 |bibcode = 2010JAHH...13..220H }}</ref> Its appearance in the north signified the arrival of the larvae of the [[wood ant]] (a food item) in spring. The beginning of summer was marked by the star's setting with the Sun in the west and the disappearance of the larvae.<ref name=mud/> The people of [[Milingimbi Island]] in Arnhem Land saw Arcturus and Muphrid as man and woman, and took the appearance of Arcturus at sunrise as a sign to go and harvest ''rakia'' or [[Eleocharis|spikerush]].<ref name=\"noctuary\">{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Diane|title=Night skies of aboriginal Australia: a noctuary|publisher=University of Sydney|location=Darlington, New South Wales|date=1998|pages=[https://archive.org/details/nightskiesofabor0000john/page/24 24, 69, 84, 112]|isbn=978-1-86451-356-1|bibcode=1998nsaa.book.....J|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/nightskiesofabor0000john/page/24}}</ref>{{rp|24,69,112}} The Wailwun of northern New South Wales knew Arcturus as ''Guembila'' \"red\".<ref name=\"noctuary\" />{{rp|84}}\n\nIn [[Inuit astronomy]], Arcturus is called the Old Man (''Uttuqalualuk'' in [[Inuit languages]]) and The First Ones (''Sivulliik'' in Inuit languages).<ref>{{cite web|title=Arcturus|url=http://www.constellation-guide.com/arcturus/|website=Constellation Guide|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Mi'kmaq]] of eastern Canada saw Arcturus as ''Kookoogw\u00e9ss'', the owl.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hagar|first=Stansbury |date=1900|title=The Celestial Bear|journal=The Journal of American Folklore|volume=13|issue=49|pages=92\u2013103|jstor=533799|doi=10.2307/533799}}</ref>\n\nArcturus had several names that described its significance to indigenous [[Polynesia]]ns. In the [[Society Islands]], Arcturus, called ''Ana-tahua-taata-metua-te-tupu-mavae'' (\"a pillar to stand by\"), was one of the ten \"pillars of the sky\", bright stars that represented the ten heavens of the [[Tahiti]]an afterlife.<!--{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=199}}--><ref name=\"makemson\"/> In [[Hawaii]], the pattern of Bo\u00f6tes was called ''Hoku-iwa'', meaning \"stars of the frigatebird\". This constellation marked the path for [[Hawaiiloa]] on his return to Hawaii from the South Pacific Ocean.{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=209}} The Hawaiians called Arcturus ''Hoku-le\u02bba''.{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=280}} It was equated to the [[Tuamotus|Tuamotuan]] constellation ''Te Kiva'', meaning \"[[frigatebird]]\", which could either represent the figure of Bo\u00f6tes or just Arcturus.{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=221}} However, Arcturus may instead be the Tuamotuan star called ''Turu''.{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=264}} The Hawaiian name for Arcturus as a single star was likely ''Hoku-le\u02bba'', which means \"star of gladness\", or \"clear star\".{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=210}} In the [[Marquesas Islands]], Arcturus was probably called ''Tau-tou'' and was the star that ruled the month approximating January. The [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and [[Moriori]] called it ''Tautoru'', a variant of the Marquesan name and a name shared with [[Orion's Belt]].{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=260}}\n\n==In culture==\n\nAs one of the [[brightest stars]] in the sky, Arcturus has been significant to observers since antiquity.\n\n===Historical cultures===\n\nPrehistoric [[Polynesian navigation|Polynesian navigators]] knew Arcturus as ''H\u014dk\u016ble\u02bba'', the \"Star of Joy\". Arcturus is the [[zenith]] star of the [[Hawaiian Islands]]. Using H\u014dk\u016ble\u02bba and other stars, the Polynesians launched their double-hulled canoes from [[Tahiti]] and the [[Marquesas Islands]]. Traveling east and north they eventually crossed the [[equator]] and reached the [[latitude]] at which Arcturus would appear directly overhead in the summer night sky. Knowing they had arrived at the exact latitude of the island chain, they sailed due west on the [[trade winds]] to landfall. If H\u014dk\u016ble\u02bba could be kept directly overhead, they landed on the southeastern shores of the [[Hawaii (island)|Big Island]] of [[Hawaii|Hawai\u02bbi]]. For a return trip to Tahiti the navigators could use Sirius, the zenith star of that island. Since 1976, the [[Polynesian Voyaging Society]]'s ''[[H\u014dk\u016ble\u02bba]]'' has crossed the Pacific Ocean many times under navigators who have incorporated this [[wayfinding]] technique in their non-instrument navigation.\n\nIn ancient [[Mesopotamia]], it was linked to the god [[Enlil]], and also known as Shudun, \"yoke\",<ref name=rogers982/> or SHU-PA of unknown derivation in the ''Three Stars Each'' [[Babylonian star catalogues]] and later [[MUL.APIN]] around 1100 BC.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Rogers | first = John H. | date = 1998 | title = Origins of the Ancient Constellations: I. The Mesopotamian Traditions | journal = Journal of the British Astronomical Association | volume = 108 | issue = 1  | pages = 9\u201328 | bibcode = 1998JBAA..108....9R}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Ancient Rome]], the star's celestial activity was supposed to portend tempestuous weather, and a personification of the star acts as narrator of the prologue to [[Plautus]]' comedy ''[[Rudens (play)|Rudens]]'' (circa 211 BC).<ref>{{cite news|author=Plautus |author-link=Plautus |title=Rudens|page= prol.&nbsp;71}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author= Lewis|author2= Short|last-author-amp= yes |author-link= Lewis and Short|work= Latin Dictionary |title= Arcturus}}</ref>\n\nIn the Hebrew scriptures Arcturus is referred to in Job 38:32.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/job/38-32.htm|website=Bible Hub|title=Job 38:32}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Middle Ages]], Arcturus was considered a [[Behenian fixed star]]<ref name=tyson1993>{{cite book | first1=Donald | last1=Tyson | last2=Freake | first2=James | date=1993 | title=Three Books of Occult Philosophy | publisher=Llewellyn Worldwide | isbn=978-0-87542-832-1 }}</ref> and attributed to the stone [[Jasper]] and the [[Plantago|plantain]] herb. [[Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa|Cornelius Agrippa]] listed its [[Kabbalah|kabbalistic]] sign [[Image:Agrippa1531 Alchameth.png]] under the alternate name ''Alchameth''.\n\nThe [[Karandavyuha Sutra|Karandavyuha sutra]], compiled at the end of the 4th century or beginning of the 5th century, names one of [[Avalokite\u015bvara|Avalokiteshvara's]] [[Samadhi|meditative absorptions]] as \"The face of Arcturus\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pacificbuddha.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Karandavyuha-Sutra.pdf|title=Karandavyuha Sutra Page 45|last=Alan Roberts|first=Peter|last2=Yeshi|first2=Tulku|date=2013|website=Pacificbuddha|publisher=84000|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOne of the possible etymologies offered for the name \"[[Arthur]]\" assumes that it is derived from \"Arcturus\" and that the early Medieval character on whom the myth of [[King Arthur]] is based was originally named for the star</ref>.<ref>Zimmer, Stefan, Die keltischen Wurzeln der Artussage: mit einer vollst\u00e4ndigen \u00dcbersetzung der \u00e4ltesten Artuserz\u00e4hlung Culhwch und Olwen, Winter, 2006, p. 37</ref><ref>Zimmer, Stefan, \"The Name of Arthur \u2013 A New Etymology \", Journal of Celtic Linguistics, Volume 13, Number 1, March 2009, University of Wales Press, pp. 131\u2013136.</ref><ref>Walter, Philippe, Faccia M. (trans.), Art\u00f9. L'orso e il re, Edizioni Arkeios, 2005, p. 74.</ref><ref>Johnson, Flint, The British sources of the abduction and Grail romances, University Press of America, 2002, pp. 38\u201339.</ref><ref>Chambers, Edmund Kerchever, Arthur of Britain, Speculum Historiale, 1964, p. 170</ref><ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0059%3Aentry%3Darcturus arct\u016brus], \nCharlton T. Lewis, Charles Short, ''A Latin Dictionary'', on Perseus</ref>\n\n===Modern cultures===\n\nArcturus achieved fame when its light was rumored to be the mechanism used to open the [[Century of Progress|1933 Chicago World's Fair]]. The star was chosen as it was thought that light from Arcturus had started its journey at about the time of the [[World's Columbian Exposition|previous Chicago World's Fair]] in 1893 (at 36.7&nbsp;light-years away, the light actually started in 1896).<ref>{{cite web|title=Century of Progress World's Fair, 1933-1934|publisher=University of Illinois-Chicago|date=January 2008|url=http://collections.carli.illinois.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/uic_cop&CISOPTR=45&CISOBOX=1&REC=1| accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nThe star is mentioned in the 1977 documentary film ''[[Powers of Ten (film)|Powers of Ten]]'', in which it is seen when a camera zooms from Earth to the whole of the known universe.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arcturus in fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=aaa465_2_593>{{Cite journal| last1=Schr\u00f6der | first1=K.-P. | last2=Cuntz | first2=M. | title=A critical test of empirical mass loss formulas applied to individual giants and supergiants | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=465 | issue=2 | pages=593\u2013601 |date=April 2007 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20066633 | bibcode=2007A&A...465..593S |arxiv = astro-ph/0702172}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aj135_3_892>{{Cite journal| display-authors=1 | last1=Carney | first1=Bruce W. | last2=Gray | first2=David F. | last3=Yong | first3=David | last4=Latham | first4=David W. | last5=Manset | first5=Nadine | last6=Zelman | first6=Rachel | last7=Laird | first7=John B. | title=Rotation and Macroturbulence in Metal-Poor Field Red Giant and Red Horizontal Branch Stars | journal=The Astronomical Journal | volume=135 | issue=3 | pages=892\u2013906 |date=March 2008 | doi=10.1088/0004-6256/135/3/892 | bibcode=2008AJ....135..892C |arxiv = 0711.4984}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"makemson\">{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Makemson |first=Maud Worcester |title= The Morning Star Rises: an account of Polynesian astronomy  |publisher=Yale University Press |date=1941 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i5giAAAAMAAJ&q=%22arcturus%22 |page=199|bibcode=1941msra.book.....M }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011>{{Cite journal|bibcode=2011ApJ...743..135R|title=Fundamental Parameters and Chemical Composition of Arcturus|journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]]|volume=743|issue=2|pages=135|date=December 2011 |author=I. Ram\u00edrez|author2=C. Allende Prieto|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/743/2/135|arxiv = 1109.4425 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\">{{cite journal | first=F. | last=van Leeuwen | title=Validation of the new Hipparcos reduction | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=474 | issue=2 | pages=653\u201364 | date=November 2007 | bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 | arxiv=0708.1752}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Arcturus}}\n* [http://www.solstation.com/stars2/arcturus.htm SolStation.com entry]\n{{Sky|14|15|39.7||19|10|56|37}}\n\n{{Stars of Bo\u00f6tes}}\n\n[[Category:Bayer objects|Bootis, Alpha]]\n[[Category:Bo\u00f6tes]]\n[[Category:Flamsteed objects|Bootis, 16]]\n[[Category:Henry Draper Catalogue objects|124897]]\n[[Category:Hipparcos objects|069673]]\n[[Category:K-type giants]]\n[[Category:Suspected variables]]\n[[Category:Hypothetical planetary systems]]\n[[Category:Stars with proper names]]\n[[Category:HR objects|5340]]\n[[Category:Durchmusterung objects|BD+19 2777]]\n[[Category:Arcturus stream]]\n[[Category:Gliese and GJ objects|0541]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Star in the constellation Bo\u00f6tes}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{Starbox begin\n | name=Arcturus\n}}\n{{Starbox image\n| image = \n     <div style=\"position: relative\">[[File:Bo\u00f6tes IAU.svg|250px|alt=Diagram showing star positions and boundaries of the Bo\u00f6tes constellation and its surroundings]]\n     <div style=\"position: absolute; left: 53.6%; top: 59.6%\">[[File:Cercle rouge 100%.svg|12px]]</div>\n     </div>\n| caption=Arcturus in the constellation of Bo\u00f6tes (circled)\n}}\n{{Starbox observe\n | epoch       =J2000\n | constell    =[[Bo\u00f6tes]]\n | pronounce   ={{IPAc-en|\u0251\u02d0r|k|\u02c8|tj|\u028a\u0259r|\u0259|s}}\n | ra          ={{RA|14|15|39.7}}<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/>\n | dec         ={{DEC|+19|10|56}}<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/>\n | appmag_v    =&minus;0.05<ref name=ducati/>\n}}\n{{Starbox character\n | class             = K0 III<ref name=gray>{{cite journal|bibcode=2003AJ....126.2048G|title=Contributions to the Nearby Stars (NStars) Project: Spectroscopy of Stars Earlier than M0 within 40 Parsecs: The Northern Sample. I|journal=The Astronomical Journal|volume=126|issue=4|pages=2048|last1=Gray|first1=R. O.|last2=Corbally|first2=C. J.|last3=Garrison|first3=R. F.|last4=McFadden|first4=M. T.|last5=Robinson|first5=P. E.|date=2003|doi=10.1086/378365|arxiv = astro-ph/0308182 }}</ref>\n | appmag_1_passband = [[J band (infrared)|J]]\n | appmag_1          = &minus;2.25<ref name=ducati>{{cite journal|bibcode=2002yCat.2237....0D|title=VizieR Online Data Catalog: Catalogue of Stellar Photometry in Johnson's 11-color system|journal=CDS/ADC Collection of Electronic Catalogues|volume=2237|pages=0|last1=Ducati|first1=J. R.|date=2002}}</ref>\n | b-v               = +1.23<ref name=ducati/>\n | u-b               = +1.28<ref name=ducati/>\n | r-i               = +0.65<ref name=ducati/>\n | v-r               =\n | variable          =\n}}\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFAFA\"\n| Note (category: variability): || H and K emission vary.\n{{Starbox astrometry\n | radial_v          =\u22125.19<ref>{{cite journal|bibcode=2008AJ....135..209M|title=Rotational and Radial Velocities for a Sample of 761 HIPPARCOS Giants and the Role of Binarity|journal=The Astronomical Journal|volume=135|issue=1|pages=209\u2013231|last1=Massarotti|first1=Alessandro|last2=Latham|first2=David W.|last3=Stefanik|first3=Robert P.|last4=Fogel|first4=Jeffrey|date=2008|doi=10.1088/0004-6256/135/1/209}}</ref>\n | prop_mo_ra        ={{val|-1093.45}}<ref name=\"Perryman1997\">{{cite web|url=http://webviz.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/VizieR-5?-source=I/239/tyc_main&HIP=69673|title=HIP 69673|work=The Hipparcos and Tycho Catalogues|author=Perryman|date=1997|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n | prop_mo_dec       ={{val|-1999.40}}<ref name=\"Perryman1997\" />\n | parallax          =88.83\n | p_error           =0.54\n | parallax_footnote =<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\" />\n | absmag_v          ={{val|-0.30|0.02}}<ref name=aj135_3_892/>\n}}\n{{Starbox detail\n | mass                ={{val|1.08|0.06}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | metal_fe            ={{val|-0.52|0.04}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | radius              ={{val|25.4|0.2}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | rotational_velocity ={{val|2.4|1.0}}<ref name=aj135_3_892/>\n | luminosity          =170<ref name=aaa465_2_593/>\n | temperature         ={{val|4286|30}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | gravity             ={{val|1.66|0.05}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n | age_gyr             ={{val|7.1|+1.5|-1.2}}<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/>\n}}\n{{Starbox catalog\n | names={{odlist | name=Alramech | name2=Alramech | name3=Abramech | B=\u03b1&nbsp;Bo\u00f6tis | F=16 Bo\u00f6tis | BD=+19\u00b0 2777 | GJ=541 | HD=124897 | HIP=69673 | HR=5340 | SAO=100944 | GCTP=3242.00 | LHS=48 }}, [[General Catalogue of Trigonometric Parallaxes|GCTP]]&nbsp;3242.00\n}}\n{{Starbox reference\n | Simbad=HD+124897\n | ARICNS =\n}}\n{{starbox sources|HIP|CCDM|HR|[http://webviz.u-strasbg.fr/viz-bin/VizieR-S?HR%205340 VizieR catalog entry]}}\n{{Starbox end}}\n\n'''Arcturus''', designation '''\u03b1&nbsp;Bo\u00f6tis''' ([[Latinisation of names|Latinized]] to '''Alpha&nbsp;Bo\u00f6tis''', abbreviated '''Alpha&nbsp;Boo''', '''\u03b1&nbsp;Boo'''), is the brightest [[star]] in the [[constellation]] of [[Bo\u00f6tes]], the [[List of brightest stars|fourth-brightest]] in the [[night sky]], and the brightest in the [[northern celestial hemisphere]]. Together with [[Spica]] and [[Denebola]] (or [[Regulus]], depending on the source), Arcturus is part of the [[Spring Triangle]] [[Asterism (astronomy)|asterism]] and, by extension, also of the [[Great Diamond]] along with the star [[Cor Caroli]].\n\nRelatively close at 36.7 [[light-year]]s from the [[Sun]], Arcturus is a [[red giant]] of spectral type K0III\u2014an aging star around 7.1 billion years old that has used up its [[Stellar core|core]] [[hydrogen]] and moved off the [[main sequence]]. It is {{Val|1.08|0.06}} times as massive [[Solar mass|as the Sun]], but has expanded to {{Val|25.4|0.2}} times [[Solar radius|its diameter]] and is around 170 times [[Solar luminosity|as luminous]].\n\n==Nomenclature==\n''\u03b1 Bo\u00f6tis'' ([[Latinisation of names|Latinised]] to ''Alpha Bo\u00f6tis'') is the star's [[Bayer designation]].\n\nThe traditional name ''Arcturus'' derives from [[Ancient Greek]] \u1f08\u03c1\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''Arktouros'') and means \"Guardian of the Bear\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3D*%29arktou%3Dros |title=\u1f08\u03c1\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 |author1=Henry George Liddell |author2=Robert Scott |work=A Greek-English Lexicon| accessdate=2019-01-16}}</ref> ultimately from \u1f04\u03c1\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 (''arktos''), \"bear\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Da%29%2Frktos |title=\u1f04\u03c1\u03ba\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 |author1=Henry George Liddell |author2=Robert Scott |work=A Greek-English Lexicon| accessdate=2019-01-16}}</ref> and \u03bf\u1f56\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''ouros''), \"watcher, guardian\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dou%29%3Dros2 |title=\u03bf\u1f56\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 |author1=Henry George Liddell |author2=Robert Scott |work=A Greek-English Lexicon| accessdate=2019-01-16}}</ref> It has been known by this name since at least the time of [[Hesiod]].<ref name=rogers982/>\n\n===Mythology===\n{{See also|Ursa Major#Mythology|Bo\u00f6tes#History and mythology}}\nOne astronomical tradition associates Arcturus with the mythology around [[Arcas]], who was about to shoot and kill his own mother [[Callisto (mythology)|Callisto]] who had been transformed into a bear. Zeus averted their imminent tragic fate by transforming the boy into the constellation Bo\u00f6tes, called Arctophylax \"bear guardian\" by the Greeks, and his mother into Ursa Major (Greek: Arctos \"the bear\"). The account is given in [[Gaius Julius Hyginus|Hyginus]]'s ''[[De Astronomica|Astronomy]]''.<ref>{{cite book|ref={{SfnRef|Eratosthenes|Hyginus|Aratus|Hard (tr.)|2015}}|author1=Eratosthenes |author2=Hyginus |author3=Aratus |others=Hard, Robin (transl.) |title=Eratosthenes and Hyginus: Constellation Myths, with Aratus's Phaenomena |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2015 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7IMSBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA36 |pages=5\u20137, 35\u201337|isbn=9780198716983 }}</ref>\n\n[[Aratus]] in his ''Phaenomena'' said that the star Arcturus lay below the belt of Arctophylax, although according to [[Ptolemy]] in the ''Almagest'' it lay between his thighs.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/bootes.htm| author=Ridpath, Ian |title=Star Tales Bo\u00f6tes |accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn alternative lore associates the name with the legend around [[Icarius (Athenian)|Icarius]], who gave the gift of wine to other men, but was murdered by them, because they had had no experience with intoxication and mistook the wine for poison. It is stated this Icarius, became Arcturus, while his dog, [[Maera (hound)|Maira]], became Canicula ([[Procyon]]), although \"Arcturus\" here may be used in the sense of the constellation rather than the star.<ref>{{harvp|Eratosthenes|Hyginus|Aratus|Hard (tr.)|2015|pp=38\u201340}}, p. 182 (note to p. 40)</ref>\n\n===Standardization===\nIn 2016, the [[International Astronomical Union]] organized a [[IAU Working Group on Star Names|Working Group on Star Names]] (WGSN)<ref name=\"WGSN\">{{cite web | url=https://www.iau.org/science/scientific_bodies/working_groups/280/ | title=IAU Working Group on Star Names (WGSN)|accessdate=22 May 2016}}</ref> to catalog and standardize proper names for stars. The WGSN's first bulletin of July 2016<ref name=\"WGSN1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/WGSN_bulletin1.pdf | title=Bulletin of the IAU Working Group on Star Names, No. 1 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> included a table of the first two batches of names approved by the WGSN; which included ''Arcturus'' for this star. It is now so entered in the IAU Catalog of Star Names.<ref name=\"IAU-CSN\">{{cite web | url=http://www.pas.rochester.edu/~emamajek/WGSN/IAU-CSN.txt | title=IAU Catalog of Star Names |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Observation==\n\nWith an [[apparent visual magnitude]] of&nbsp;&minus;0.05, Arcturus is the brightest star in the [[northern celestial hemisphere]] and the [[list of brightest stars|fourth-brightest star]] in the night sky,<ref name=\"100greatest\">{{cite book | title=The Hundred Greatest Stars | author=Kaler, James B. | date=2002 | publisher=Copernicus Books | location=New York, New York | isbn=978-0-387-95436-3 | page=21}}</ref> after [[Sirius]] (&minus;1.46&nbsp;apparent magnitude), [[Canopus (star)|Canopus]] (&minus;0.72) and [[\u03b1 Centauri]] (combined magnitude of &minus;0.27). However, \u03b1 Centauri AB is a [[binary star]], whose components are both fainter than Arcturus. This makes Arcturus the third-brightest individual star, just ahead of \u03b1 Centauri&nbsp;A (officially named ''Rigil Kentaurus''), whose apparent magnitude {{nobr|is &minus;0.01}}.<ref name=schaaf>{{cite book| first=Fred | last=Schaaf | date=2008 | title=The Brightest Stars: Discovering the Universe Through the Sky's Most Brilliant Stars | pages=126\u201336 | publisher=John Wiley and Sons|location=Hoboken, New Jersey | isbn=978-0-471-70410-2 | bibcode=2008bsdu.book.....S }}</ref> The French mathematician and astronomer [[Jean-Baptiste Morin (mathematician)|Jean-Baptiste Morin]] observed Arcturus in the daytime with a telescope in 1635, a first for any star other than the [[Sun]] and [[supernova]]e.  Arcturus has been seen at or just before sunset with the naked eye.<ref name=schaaf/>\n\nArcturus is visible from both of [[Earth]]'s hemispheres as it is located 19\u00b0 north of the [[celestial equator]]. The star [[culmination|culminates]] at midnight on 27 April, and at 9 p.m. on June 10 being visible during the late northern spring or the southern autumn.<ref>Schaaf, p. 257.</ref> From the [[northern hemisphere]], an easy way to find Arcturus is to follow the arc of the handle of the [[Big Dipper]] (or Plough). By continuing in this path, one can find [[Spica]], \"Arc to Arcturus, then spike (or speed on) to Spica\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rao |first1=Joe |title=Arc to Arcturus, Speed on to Spica |url=https://www.space.com/3953-arc-arcturus-speed-spica.html |accessdate=14 August 2018 |work=Space.com |date=June 15, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Follow the arc to Arcturus, and drive a spike to Spica {{!}} EarthSky.org |url=http://earthsky.org/tonight/follow-the-arc-to-arcturus |accessdate=14 August 2018 |work=earthsky.org |date=April 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPtolemy described Arcturus as ''subrufa'' (\"slightly red\"): it has a B-V color index of +1.23, roughly midway between [[Pollux (star)|Pollux]] (B-V +1.00) and [[Aldebaran]] (B-V +1.54).<ref name=schaaf/>\n\n[[\u03b7 Bo\u00f6tis]], or Muphrid, is only 3.3 [[light-year]]s distant from Arcturus, and would have a visual magnitude \u22122.5, about as bright as [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] from [[Earth]], whereas an observer on the former system would find Arcturus as bright as [[Venus]] as seen from Earth.<ref name=schaaf/>\n\nIn 1984, the 90 cm (36-inch) reflecting [[Yapp telescope]] at Herstmonceux was tested with an [[echelle spectrograph]] from [[Queen's University Belfast]] and a CCD camera. Observations of the stars Arcturus and [[Deneb]] (Alpha Cygni) were conducted in the summer of 1984.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite journal |bibcode=1985A&A...145..321B |title=High dispersion spectroscopy trials using an echelle spectrograph with CCD camera |journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics |volume=145 |pages=321 |last1=Bates |first1=B. |last2=McKeith |first2=C. D. |last3=Jorden |first3=P. R. |last4=Van Breda |first4=I. G. |year=1985 }}</ref>\n\n==Physical characteristics==\n[[File:Arcturus (optical).png|thumb|right|275 px|Optical image of Arcturus (DSS2 / MAST / STScI / NASA)]]\nBased upon an annual [[stellar parallax|parallax]] shift of 88.83&nbsp;[[Minute and second of arc#Astronomy|milliarcseconds]] as measured by the [[Hipparcos]] satellite, Arcturus is {{Convert|11.26|pc|ly|abbr=off|lk=on|order=flip}} from the Sun. The parallax [[margin of error]] is 0.54 milliarcseconds, translating to a distance margin of error of \u00b1{{Convert|0.069|pc|ly|abbr=off|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\"/> Because of its proximity, Arcturus has a high [[proper motion]], two [[Minute and second of arc#Astronomy|arcseconds]] a year, greater than any [[first magnitude star]] other than \u03b1&nbsp;Centauri.\n\nArcturus is moving rapidly ({{nowrap|122 km/s}}) relative to the Sun, and is now almost at its closest point to the Sun. Closest approach will happen in about 4,000 years, when the star will be a few hundredths of a light-year closer to Earth than it is today. (In antiquity, Arcturus was closer to the centre of the constellation.<ref name=rogers982>{{cite journal | last = Rogers | first = John H. | date = 1998 | title = Origins of the Ancient Constellations: II. The Mediterranean Traditions | journal = Journal of the British Astronomical Association | volume = 108 | issue = 2 | pages = 79\u201389 | bibcode = 1998JBAA..108...79R}}</ref>) Arcturus is thought to be an [[old-disk star]], and appears to be moving with a group of 52 other such stars, known as the [[Arcturus stream]].<ref name=ramya>{{cite journal|bibcode=2012MNRAS.425.3188R|arxiv=1207.0767|title=Chemical compositions of stars in two stellar streams from the Galactic thick disc|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=425|issue=4|pages=3188|last1=Ramya|first1=P.|last2=Reddy|first2=Bacham E.|last3=Lambert|first3=David L.|date=2012|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2966.2012.21677.x}}</ref>\n\nWith an [[absolute magnitude]] of \u22120.30, Arcturus is, together with [[Vega]] and Sirius, one of the most luminous stars in the Sun's neighborhood. It is about 110 times brighter than the Sun in visible light wavelengths, but this underestimates its strength as much of the light it gives off is in the [[infrared]]; total ([[Bolometric correction|bolometric]]) power output is about 180&nbsp;times that of the Sun.  With a near-infrared [[J band (infrared)|J band]] [[Magnitude (astronomy)|magnitude]] of \u22122.2, only [[Betelgeuse]] (\u22122.9) and [[R Doradus]] (\u22122.6) are brighter.  The lower output in visible light is due to a lower [[Luminous efficacy|efficacy]] as the star has a lower [[effective temperature|surface temperature]] than the Sun.\n\nArcturus is an [[stellar evolution|evolved]] [[red giant]] star with a [[stellar classification]] of K0&nbsp;III. As the brightest K-type [[Giant star#Red giants|giant]] in the sky, it was the subject of an [[spectral atlas|atlas]] of its visible [[stellar spectrum|spectrum]], made from [[photographic plate|photographic]] spectra taken with the [[Reflecting telescope#Coud\u00e9|coud\u00e9]] [[spectrograph]] of the [[Mount Wilson Observatory|Mt. Wilson 2.5m telescope]] published in 1968,<ref>{{cite book | last=Griffin | first=R. E. |last2=Griffin | first2=R. | title=A photometric atlas of the spectrum of Arcturus, \u03bb\u03bb3600-8825\u00c5 | publisher=Cambridge Philosophical Society |location=Cambridge | date=1968 | bibcode=1968pmas.book.....G }}</ref> a key reference work for stellar spectroscopy. Subsequent spectral atlases<ref>{{cite book | last=Hinkle | first=Kenneth |last2=Wallace | first2=Lloyd | last3=Valenti | first3=Jeff | last4=Harmer | first4=Dianne | title=Visible and Near Infrared Atlas of the Arcturus Spectrum 3727-9300 \u00c5 | bibcode=2000vnia.book.....H | publisher=[[Astronomical Society of the Pacific]] | location=San Francisco | isbn=978-1-58381-037-8 | date=2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Hinkle | first=Kenneth |last2=Wallace | first2=Lloyd | last3=Livingston |first3=William Charles | title=Infrared atlas of the Arcturus spectrum, 0.9-5.3 microns | bibcode=1995iaas.book.....H | publisher=Astronomical Society of the Pacific | location=San Francisco | date=1995 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Hinkle | first=Kenneth |last2=Wallace | first2=Lloyd | last3=Valenti |first3=Jeff | last4=Ayres | first4=Thomas | title=Ultraviolet Atlas of the Arcturus Spectrum, 1150-3800 \u00c5 | bibcode=2005uaas.book.....H | publisher=Astronomical Society of the Pacific | location=San Francisco | date=2005 }}</ref> with greater wavelength coverage and superior [[signal-to-noise ratio]] made with digital detectors have supplanted the older work, but the Arcturus spectrum remains an important standard for stellar spectroscopy.\n\nAs a single star, the mass of Arcturus cannot be measured directly, but models suggest it is slightly larger than that of the Sun. Evolutionary matching to the observed physical parameters gives a mass of {{Val|1.08|0.06|u=solar mass}},<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/> while the oxygen isotope ratio for a first [[dredge-up]] star gives a mass of {{solar mass|1.2}}.<ref name=abia>{{cite journal|bibcode=2012A&A...548A..55A|arxiv=1210.1160|title=Carbon and oxygen isotopic ratios in Arcturus and Aldebaran. Constraining the parameters for non-convective mixing on the red giant branch|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|volume=548|pages=A55|last1=Abia|first1=C.|last2=Palmerini|first2=S.|last3=Busso|first3=M.|last4=Cristallo|first4=S.|date=2012|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201220148}}</ref> The star displays [[Stellar magnetic field|magnetic activity]] that is heating the [[corona]]l structures, and it undergoes a [[Solar cycle|solar-type magnetic cycle]] with a duration that is probably less than 14 years. A weak magnetic field has been detected in the [[photosphere]] with a strength of around half a [[Gauss (unit)|gauss]]. The magnetic activity appears to lie along four latitudes and is rotationally-modulated.<ref name=Sennhauser2011>{{cite journal | title=First detection of a weak magnetic field on the giant Arcturus: remnants of a solar dynamo? | last1=Sennhauser | first1=C. | last2=Berdyugina | first2=S. V. | journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics | volume=529 | id=A100 | pages=6 | date=May 2011 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201015445 | bibcode=2011A&A...529A.100S }}</ref>\n\nArcturus is estimated to be around 6 billion to 8.5 billion years old,<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/> but there is some uncertainty about its evolutionary status.<ref name=Pavlenko2008/> Based upon the [[Color index|color characteristics]] of Arcturus, it is currently ascending the [[red-giant branch]] and will continue to do so until it accumulates a large enough degenerate helium [[Stellar core|core]] to ignite the [[helium flash]].<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011/> It has likely exhausted the [[hydrogen]] from its core and is now in its active [[red giant|hydrogen shell burning]] phase. However, Charbonnel et al. (1998) placed it slightly above the [[horizontal branch]], and suggested it has already completed the helium flash stage.<ref name=Pavlenko2008>{{cite journal | title=The carbon abundance and <sup>12</sup>C/<sup>13</sup>C isotopic ratio in the atmosphere of Arcturus from 2.3 \u00b5m CO bands | last1=Pavlenko | first1=Ya. V. | journal=Astronomy Reports | volume=52 | issue=9 | pages=749\u2013759 | date=September 2008 | doi=10.1134/S1063772908090060 | bibcode=2008ARep...52..749P | arxiv=0807.3667 }}</ref>\n\n===Oscillations===\nAs one of the brightest stars in the sky, Arcturus has been the subject of a number of studies in the emerging field of [[asteroseismology]]. Belmonte and colleagues carried out a radial velocity (Doppler shift of spectral lines) study of the star in April and May 1988, which showed variability with a frequency of the order of a few micro[[hertz]] (\u03bcHz), the highest peak corresponding to 4.3&nbsp;\u03bcHz (2.7&nbsp;days) with an amplitude of 60 ms<sup>\u22121</sup>, with a [[frequency separation]] of c.&nbsp;5&nbsp;\u03bcHz. They suggested that the most plausible explanation for the variability of Arcturus is stellar oscillations.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Belmonte, J. A.|author2=Jones, A. R.|author3=Palle, P. L.|author4=Roca Cortes, T.|date=1990|title=Acoustic oscillations in the K2 III star Arcturus|journal=Astrophysics and Space Science|volume=169|issue=1\u20132|pages=77\u201384|issn=0004-640X|doi=10.1007/BF00640689 |bibcode=1990Ap&SS.169...77B}}</ref>\n\nAsteroseismological measurements allow direct calculation of the mass and radius, giving values of {{Val|0.8|0.2|u=solar mass}} and {{Val|27.9|3.4|ul=solar radius}}. This form of modelling is still relatively inaccurate, but a useful check on other models.<ref name=kallinger>{{cite journal|bibcode=2010A&A...509A..77K|title=Oscillating red giants in the CoRoT exofield: Asteroseismic mass and radius determination|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=509|pages=A77|last1=Kallinger|first1=T.|last2=Weiss|first2=W. W.|last3=Barban|first3=C.|last4=Baudin|first4=F.|last5=Cameron|first5=C.|last6=Carrier|first6=F.|last7=De Ridder|first7=J.|last8=Goupil|first8=M.-J.|last9=Gruberbauer|first9=M.|last10=Hatzes|first10=A.|last11=Hekker|first11=S.|last12=Samadi|first12=R.|last13=Deleuil|first13=M.|date=2010|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/200811437|arxiv=0811.4674}}</ref>\n\n===Element abundance===\nAstronomers term \"metals\" those elements with higher [[atomic number]]s than [[helium]]. Arcturus has an enrichment of [[alpha elements]] relative to [[iron]] but only about a third of solar [[metallicity]]. Arcturus is possibly a [[Population II star]].<ref name=schaaf/>\n\n===Possible planetary system===\n''Hipparcos'' also suggested that Arcturus is a [[binary star]], with the companion about twenty times dimmer than the primary and orbiting close enough to be at the very limits of humans' current ability to make it out. Recent results remain inconclusive, but do support the marginal ''Hipparcos'' detection of a binary companion.<ref>{{Cite journal| first1=T.|last1=Verhoelst|first2=P. J.|display-authors= 4|last2= Bord\u00e9|first3=G.|last3=Perrin|first4=L.|last4=Decin|title=Is Arcturus a well-understood K giant?|journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics|date=2005|volume=435|pages=289\u2013301|doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20042356|last5= Eriksson|first5=K.|last6=Ridgway|first6=S. T.|last7=Schuller|first7=P. A.|last8=Traub|first8=W. A.|last9=Millan-Gabet|first9=R.|last10=Lacasse|first10=M. G.|last11=Waelkens|first11=C.|  postscript=<!--None-->|bibcode=2005A&A...435..289V|arxiv=astro-ph/0501669}}, and see references therein.</ref>\n\nIn 1993, radial velocity measurements of Aldebaran, Arcturus and Pollux showed that Arcturus exhibited a long-period radial velocity oscillation, which could be interpreted as a ''substellar companion''. This [[substellar object]] would be nearly 12&nbsp;times the [[mass of Jupiter]] and be located roughly at the same orbital distance from Arcturus as the Earth is from the Sun, at 1.1&nbsp;[[astronomical unit]]s. However, all three stars surveyed showed similar oscillations yielding similar companion masses, and the authors concluded that the variation was likely to be intrinsic to the star rather than due to the gravitational effect of a companion. So far no substellar companion has been confirmed.<ref name=Kgiants>{{cite journal|doi=10.1086/173002|title=Long-period radial velocity variations in three K giants|author=Hatzes, A.|author2=Cochran, W.|journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]]|volume=413|issue = 1|pages=339\u2013348|date=August 1993|bibcode=1993ApJ...413..339H}}</ref>\n<!--\n{{PlanetboxOrbit begin}}\n{{PlanetboxOrbit hypothetical\n| exoplanet = [[Arcturus b|b]]\n| mass = 11.7\n| period = 233\n| semimajor = 1.1\n| eccentricity = 0.147\n}}\n{{PlanetboxOrbit end}}\nPut the starbox in once a planet has been confirmed, if it is a planet and not a brown dwarf.-->\n\n==Other names==\n\n=== In Arabic ===\nIn [[Arabic]], Arcturus is one of two stars called ''al-sim\u0101k'' \"the uplifted ones\" (the other is [[Spica]]). Arcturus is specified as \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0643 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0645\u062d ''as-sim\u0101k ar-r\u0101mi\u0127'' \"the uplifted one of the lancer\". The term ''Al Simak Al Ramih'' has appeared in Al Achsasi Al Mouakket catalogue (translated into [[Latin]] as ''Al Simak Lanceator'').<ref>{{cite journal|last=Knobel|first=E. B.|title=Al Achsasi Al Mouakket, on a catalogue of stars in the Calendarium of Mohammad Al Achsasi Al Mouakket|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society|volume=55|issue=8|page=429|date=June 1895|bibcode= 1895MNRAS..55..429K|doi=10.1093/mnras/55.8.429}}</ref>\n\nThis has been variously [[Romanization|romanized]] in the past, leading to obsolete variants such as ''Aramec'' and ''Azimech''. For example, the name ''Alramih'' is used in [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[A Treatise on the Astrolabe]]'' (1391). Another Arabic name is ''Haris-el-sema'', from ''\u062d\u0627\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0621'' ''\u0127\u0101ris al-sam\u0101\u2019'' \"the keeper of heaven\".<ref name=arabicstar>{{cite web|url=http://www.jas.org.jo/arabic/alma.html|title= List of the 25&nbsp;brightest stars|website = Jordanian Astronomical Society|accessdate=March 28, 2007}}</ref><ref name=allen>{{cite book|author=Allen, Richard Hinckley |title=Star-names and their meanings|date=1936|pages= 100\u2013101}}</ref><ref name=arabicdict>{{cite book|author=Wehr, Hans |editor=Cowan, J. Milton |title=A dictionary of modern written Arabic|date=1994}}</ref> or ''\u062d\u0627\u0631\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0645\u0627\u0644'' ''\u0127\u0101ris al-sham\u0101l\u2019'' \"the keeper of north\".<ref>{{cite journal|author=Davis Jr., G. A.|bibcode=1944PA.....52....8D |title=The Pronunciations, Derivations, and Meanings of a Selected List of Star Names|journal=Popular Astronomy|volume= 52|date=  October 3, 1944|page= 13}}</ref>\n\nArcturus was once again called by its classical name from the Renaissance onwards.<ref>{{cite book |author= Kunitzsch, Paul |author2= Smart, Tim|date = 2006|title = A Dictionary of Modern star Names: A Short Guide to 254 Star Names and Their Derivations |edition = 2nd rev.  |publisher = [[Sky Publishing Corporation|Sky Pub]] |location = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts|MA]] |isbn = 978-1-931559-44-7 |page = 19}}</ref>\n\n===Asia===\nIn [[Chinese astronomy]], Arcturus is called ''Da Jiao'' ({{zh|c=\u5927\u89d2|p=D\u00e0ji\u01ceo|l=great horn}}), because it is the brightest star in the [[Chinese constellation]] called ''[[Horn (Chinese constellation)|Jiao Xiu]]'' ({{zh|c=\u89d2\u5bbf|p=Ji\u01ceo Xi\u01d4|l=horn star|links=no}}). Later it became a part of another constellation ''[[Neck (Chinese constellation)|Kang Xiu]]'' ({{zh|c=\u4ea2\u5bbf|p=K\u00e0ng Xi\u01d4|links=no}}).\n\nIn Indian [[Astrology]] or [[Hindu astrology|Vedic Astrology]] or [[Sidereal Astrology]], Arcturus is called ''[[Swati the Star|Swati]]'' which is a word meaning \"very beneficent\" derived from the language [[Sanskrit]]. It is the [[eponymous]] star of one of the [[nakshatra]]s (lunar mansions) of [[Hindu astrology]].\n\n===Other languages===\nThe [[Wotjobaluk people|Wotjobaluk]] [[Koori]] people of southeastern Australia knew Arcturus as ''Marpean-kurrk'', mother of ''Djuit'' ([[Antares]]) and another star in Bo\u00f6tes, ''Weet-kurrk''<ref name=mud>{{Cite book|last=Mudrooroo|title=Aboriginal mythology : an A-Z spanning the history of aboriginal mythology from the earliest legends to the present day|publisher=HarperCollins|location=London|date= 1994|page=5|isbn=978-1-85538-306-7}}</ref> (Muphrid).<ref name=hamacher10>{{cite journal|author=Hamacher, Duane W.|author2=Frew, David J. |date=2010|title= An Aboriginal Australian Record of the Great Eruption of Eta Carinae|journal=Journal of Astronomical History & Heritage |volume=13|issue=3|pages= 220\u201334|arxiv = 1010.4610 |bibcode = 2010JAHH...13..220H }}</ref> Its appearance in the north signified the arrival of the larvae of the [[wood ant]] (a food item) in spring. The beginning of summer was marked by the star's setting with the Sun in the west and the disappearance of the larvae.<ref name=mud/> The people of [[Milingimbi Island]] in Arnhem Land saw Arcturus and Muphrid as man and woman, and took the appearance of Arcturus at sunrise as a sign to go and harvest ''rakia'' or [[Eleocharis|spikerush]].<ref name=\"noctuary\">{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Diane|title=Night skies of aboriginal Australia: a noctuary|publisher=University of Sydney|location=Darlington, New South Wales|date=1998|pages=[https://archive.org/details/nightskiesofabor0000john/page/24 24, 69, 84, 112]|isbn=978-1-86451-356-1|bibcode=1998nsaa.book.....J|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/nightskiesofabor0000john/page/24}}</ref>{{rp|24,69,112}} The Wailwun of northern New South Wales knew Arcturus as ''Guembila'' \"red\".<ref name=\"noctuary\" />{{rp|84}}\n\nIn [[Inuit astronomy]], Arcturus is called the Old Man (''Uttuqalualuk'' in [[Inuit languages]]) and The First Ones (''Sivulliik'' in Inuit languages).<ref>{{cite web|title=Arcturus|url=http://www.constellation-guide.com/arcturus/|website=Constellation Guide|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Mi'kmaq]] of eastern Canada saw Arcturus as ''Kookoogw\u00e9ss'', the owl.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hagar|first=Stansbury |date=1900|title=The Celestial Bear|journal=The Journal of American Folklore|volume=13|issue=49|pages=92\u2013103|jstor=533799|doi=10.2307/533799}}</ref>\n\nArcturus had several names that described its significance to indigenous [[Polynesia]]ns. In the [[Society Islands]], Arcturus, called ''Ana-tahua-taata-metua-te-tupu-mavae'' (\"a pillar to stand by\"), was one of the ten \"pillars of the sky\", bright stars that represented the ten heavens of the [[Tahiti]]an afterlife.<!--{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=199}}--><ref name=\"makemson\"/> In [[Hawaii]], the pattern of Bo\u00f6tes was called ''Hoku-iwa'', meaning \"stars of the frigatebird\". This constellation marked the path for [[Hawaiiloa]] on his return to Hawaii from the South Pacific Ocean.{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=209}} The Hawaiians called Arcturus ''Hoku-le\u02bba''.{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=280}} It was equated to the [[Tuamotus|Tuamotuan]] constellation ''Te Kiva'', meaning \"[[frigatebird]]\", which could either represent the figure of Bo\u00f6tes or just Arcturus.{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=221}} However, Arcturus may instead be the Tuamotuan star called ''Turu''.{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=264}} The Hawaiian name for Arcturus as a single star was likely ''Hoku-le\u02bba'', which means \"star of gladness\", or \"clear star\".{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=210}} In the [[Marquesas Islands]], Arcturus was probably called ''Tau-tou'' and was the star that ruled the month approximating January. The [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and [[Moriori]] called it ''Tautoru'', a variant of the Marquesan name and a name shared with [[Orion's Belt]].{{sfn|Makemson|1941|p=260}}\n\n==In culture==\n\nAs one of the [[brightest stars]] in the sky, Arcturus has been significant to observers since antiquity.\n\n===Historical cultures===\n\nPrehistoric [[Polynesian navigation|Polynesian navigators]] knew Arcturus as ''H\u014dk\u016ble\u02bba'', the \"Star of Joy\". Arcturus is the [[zenith]] star of the [[Hawaiian Islands]]. Using H\u014dk\u016ble\u02bba and other stars, the Polynesians launched their double-hulled canoes from [[Tahiti]] and the [[Marquesas Islands]]. Traveling east and north they eventually crossed the [[equator]] and reached the [[latitude]] at which Arcturus would appear directly overhead in the summer night sky. Knowing they had arrived at the exact latitude of the island chain, they sailed due west on the [[trade winds]] to landfall. If H\u014dk\u016ble\u02bba could be kept directly overhead, they landed on the southeastern shores of the [[Hawaii (island)|Big Island]] of [[Hawaii|Hawai\u02bbi]]. For a return trip to Tahiti the navigators could use Sirius, the zenith star of that island. Since 1976, the [[Polynesian Voyaging Society]]'s ''[[H\u014dk\u016ble\u02bba]]'' has crossed the Pacific Ocean many times under navigators who have incorporated this [[wayfinding]] technique in their non-instrument navigation.\n\nIn ancient [[Mesopotamia]], it was linked to the god [[Enlil]], and also known as Shudun, \"yoke\",<ref name=rogers982/> or SHU-PA of unknown derivation in the ''Three Stars Each'' [[Babylonian star catalogues]] and later [[MUL.APIN]] around 1100 BC.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Rogers | first = John H. | date = 1998 | title = Origins of the Ancient Constellations: I. The Mesopotamian Traditions | journal = Journal of the British Astronomical Association | volume = 108 | issue = 1  | pages = 9\u201328 | bibcode = 1998JBAA..108....9R}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Ancient Rome]], the star's celestial activity was supposed to portend tempestuous weather, and a personification of the star acts as narrator of the prologue to [[Plautus]]' comedy ''[[Rudens (play)|Rudens]]'' (circa 211 BC).<ref>{{cite news|author=Plautus |author-link=Plautus |title=Rudens|page= prol.&nbsp;71}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author= Lewis|author2= Short|last-author-amp= yes |author-link= Lewis and Short|work= Latin Dictionary |title= Arcturus}}</ref>\n\nIn the Hebrew scriptures Arcturus is referred to in Job 38:32.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/job/38-32.htm|website=Bible Hub|title=Job 38:32}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Middle Ages]], Arcturus was considered a [[Behenian fixed star]]<ref name=tyson1993>{{cite book | first1=Donald | last1=Tyson | last2=Freake | first2=James | date=1993 | title=Three Books of Occult Philosophy | publisher=Llewellyn Worldwide | isbn=978-0-87542-832-1 }}</ref> and attributed to the stone [[Jasper]] and the [[Plantago|plantain]] herb. [[Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa|Cornelius Agrippa]] listed its [[Kabbalah|kabbalistic]] sign [[Image:Agrippa1531 Alchameth.png]] under the alternate name ''Alchameth''.\n\nThe [[Karandavyuha Sutra|Karandavyuha sutra]], compiled at the end of the 4th century or beginning of the 5th century, names one of [[Avalokite\u015bvara|Avalokiteshvara's]] [[Samadhi|meditative absorptions]] as \"The face of Arcturus\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pacificbuddha.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Karandavyuha-Sutra.pdf|title=Karandavyuha Sutra Page 45|last=Alan Roberts|first=Peter|last2=Yeshi|first2=Tulku|date=2013|website=Pacificbuddha|publisher=84000|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOne of the possible etymologies offered for the name \"[[Arthur]]\" assumes that it is derived from \"Arcturus\" and that the early Medieval character on whom the myth of [[King Arthur]] is based was originally named for the star </ref><ref>Zimmer, Stefan, Die keltischen Wurzeln der Artussage: mit einer vollst\u00e4ndigen \u00dcbersetzung der \u00e4ltesten Artuserz\u00e4hlung Culhwch und Olwen, Winter, 2006, p. 37</ref><ref>Zimmer, Stefan, \"The Name of Arthur \u2013 A New Etymology \", Journal of Celtic Linguistics, Volume 13, Number 1, March 2009, University of Wales Press, pp. 131\u2013136.</ref><ref>Walter, Philippe, Faccia M. (trans.), Art\u00f9. L'orso e il re, Edizioni Arkeios, 2005, p. 74.</ref><ref>Johnson, Flint, The British sources of the abduction and Grail romances, University Press of America, 2002, pp. 38\u201339.</ref><ref>Chambers, Edmund Kerchever, Arthur of Britain, Speculum Historiale, 1964, p. 170</ref> <ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0059%3Aentry%3Darcturus arct\u016brus], \nCharlton T. Lewis, Charles Short, ''A Latin Dictionary'', on Perseus</ref>.\n\n===Modern cultures===\n\nArcturus achieved fame when its light was rumored to be the mechanism used to open the [[Century of Progress|1933 Chicago World's Fair]]. The star was chosen as it was thought that light from Arcturus had started its journey at about the time of the [[World's Columbian Exposition|previous Chicago World's Fair]] in 1893 (at 36.7&nbsp;light-years away, the light actually started in 1896).<ref>{{cite web|title=Century of Progress World's Fair, 1933-1934|publisher=University of Illinois-Chicago|date=January 2008|url=http://collections.carli.illinois.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/uic_cop&CISOPTR=45&CISOBOX=1&REC=1| accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref>\n\nThe star is mentioned in the 1977 documentary film ''[[Powers of Ten (film)|Powers of Ten]]'', in which it is seen when a camera zooms from Earth to the whole of the known universe.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Arcturus in fiction]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=aaa465_2_593>{{Cite journal| last1=Schr\u00f6der | first1=K.-P. | last2=Cuntz | first2=M. | title=A critical test of empirical mass loss formulas applied to individual giants and supergiants | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=465 | issue=2 | pages=593\u2013601 |date=April 2007 | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20066633 | bibcode=2007A&A...465..593S |arxiv = astro-ph/0702172}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aj135_3_892>{{Cite journal| display-authors=1 | last1=Carney | first1=Bruce W. | last2=Gray | first2=David F. | last3=Yong | first3=David | last4=Latham | first4=David W. | last5=Manset | first5=Nadine | last6=Zelman | first6=Rachel | last7=Laird | first7=John B. | title=Rotation and Macroturbulence in Metal-Poor Field Red Giant and Red Horizontal Branch Stars | journal=The Astronomical Journal | volume=135 | issue=3 | pages=892\u2013906 |date=March 2008 | doi=10.1088/0004-6256/135/3/892 | bibcode=2008AJ....135..892C |arxiv = 0711.4984}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"makemson\">{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Makemson |first=Maud Worcester |title= The Morning Star Rises: an account of Polynesian astronomy  |publisher=Yale University Press |date=1941 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i5giAAAAMAAJ&q=%22arcturus%22 |page=199|bibcode=1941msra.book.....M }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ramirez_prieto_2011>{{Cite journal|bibcode=2011ApJ...743..135R|title=Fundamental Parameters and Chemical Composition of Arcturus|journal=[[The Astrophysical Journal]]|volume=743|issue=2|pages=135|date=December 2011 |author=I. Ram\u00edrez|author2=C. Allende Prieto|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/743/2/135|arxiv = 1109.4425 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"vanLeeuwen2007\">{{cite journal | first=F. | last=van Leeuwen | title=Validation of the new Hipparcos reduction | journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume=474 | issue=2 | pages=653\u201364 | date=November 2007 | bibcode=2007A&A...474..653V | doi=10.1051/0004-6361:20078357 | arxiv=0708.1752}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Arcturus}}\n* [http://www.solstation.com/stars2/arcturus.htm SolStation.com entry]\n{{Sky|14|15|39.7||19|10|56|37}}\n\n{{Stars of Bo\u00f6tes}}